animal.description:
Hi. My name is Angel. My foster mom took care of me for nine months while running wild and not able to be caught. I got pregnant and my foster mom never gave up on me. She took care of me and my babies until we could all be safely caught and placed into foster homes. My babies have all found forever homes and now it's my turn. I need a home where someone is home most of the time to care for me and gain my trust. I am very sweet but very scared. No children please as I am terrified of every one but my foster mom and I need someone that will patient with me, love me and give me a chance. I cannot be let out because I will run away and you won't catch me. I can dig out too so I need a fence I can't get out of or under. I would love to be someone's house dog and be treated like a queen. My former family was very mean to me and that's why I am scared of people. The vet says I am about 2 years old.

My adoption fee is $200 and will include all my vaccines, spay and microchip. Fill out an app at www.soca-fbc.org under the adoptables tab.

5. Bring treats

Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility..

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description: Say hello to Elijah! This ten-year-old pit bull is a total sweetheart who loves to sleep. In fact, his foster mom says if he were one of the Seven Dwarves, he would be Sleepy! He would love to rest his head in his forever home. Elijah is a great cuddler. He loves being by his humans at all times, but also enjoys a break from them to lay in the grass or dirt. He is blind but hears pretty well, so slow introductions are a must for him. But once he knows someone, he's a friend for life! Elijah is housetrained and does well on a leash once he gets comfortable with his surroundings. He also gets along well with other dogs and kids, but only with a slow introduction so he's not startled or scared. Elijah is a very affectionate boy who will wander around the house looking for his people, and then is so happy when he finds them. An ideal home for him would be a relaxed one so he's not startled. He loves bonding with his humans so he'd love a family that could be with him most of the time. This old boy deserves the perfect forever home. Could that be with you? Apply to adopt Elijah today! This pet is available for pre-adoption and may not be officially ready for adoption, as it is still undergoing medical treatment. Depending on the medical status, a Meet and Greet may be put on hold until they can safely participate in a meeting with potential adopters. In some cases, this pet may be able to move to its forever home while it is still under the medical care of Dallas Pets Alive. If you are interested in learning more, apply now and one of our Adoption Counselors will discuss the options available so you can bring home your new furry family member! Applications are processed in the order in which they are received; please be aware that this pet may have interested applicants ahead of you. All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ . For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org.

animal.description: This handsome tall drink of water is Rio! His interests include fetch, swimming, fetch, treats, fetch, and gently leaning into your leg for pets. We should also mention that he loves playing fetch and will regularly do leaps and flips in the air trying to catch the ball. And he's really great at bringing the ball back to you and dropping it. If he thinks you don't see the ball on the ground, he'll politely pick it up and set it in your lap. Rio manages to keep the game going with even the laziest of tennis ball throwers! True to his name, Rio also really LOVES being in the water! Whether you're hosing him off or taking him for a dip in a pool or creek, he'll take all the water time he can get. And while he is incredibly energetic when playing with a ball or in the water, when he's all tuckered out, he's happy to hang out with his person and snuggling. Rio can be aloof with people he doesn't know, but he warms up quickly and before long he's asking for belly rubs and cuddles. Rio's a big guy, but he is very easy to walk on leash and enjoys going a nice quiet walk around the neighborhood, taking in all the sights and smells while staying by your side at a nice pace. He's also a smart pup who sits politely for treats and recently became TOP Dog Ready, which means he has already learned all the skills in his training plan in APA!'s Total Obedience Program. The Total Obedience Program (TOP) is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Rio has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! Dogs in the program learn skills including sitting calmly when approached by strangers, calmly walking past another dog, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' and coming when called. In addition, Rio has also learned 'Place'. Rio has worked hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Rio after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 In addition to his TOP Dog training, Rio is a pro at crate training and is perfectly content to wait patiently for you to come home and play a game of fetch. While he's never met a tennis ball he doesn't like, he can be pretty picky about his canine friends and would do best as an only dog in an adult-only home. Rio's an easy friend who's easy to please and he's more than ready to move on to his forever home. Come meet this handsome guy today! Follow Rio on Instagram @riosbigadventure and @rio.plus.1

animal.description:
Maybe were biased but we feel Maximus is the handsomest seven year-old Pitty around! This big smile has been through SO MUCH and has overcome a really long battle of neglect. He was very sick when we rescued him but is better now! Maximus does have heart failure but can still play and walk like the champ he is. But that has not stopped him from giving snuggles, love and gently romping around. Hes completely trained too! Were talking: leash trained, house trained, he knows things like sit and even stay! Hell even sit still for you while you clip his nails! He loves going for short walks. He is not good with small pets of any kind. Maximus doesnt need a fence since he only needs a short amount of exercise. He is a big boy close to 80 lbs. Would do best in a home as the only male dog. He's wonderful with females though, you could say he loves the ladies! This big boy has lots of snuggles and love to give. Please help us find a good home for him!

The adoption fee for this handsome man is $150. He has been neutered, microchipped and is up to date on vaccines!

Want to meet Maximus? Submit an adoption application and someone will be in touch to schedule a meet n greet to see if hes the right match for you!

animal.description: Miss Olivia, aka Sweet Potato, is my name. Im desperately in need of a foster home. I was dumped at a high kill shelter. A rescue agreed to take me when I was just an hour away from being euthanized. I was so sick though I didnt even realize what was going on. I was taken immediately to the emergency vet where they stabilized my condition and was then transferred to the rescues regular vet. Theyve run a bunch of tests and it was found that I had a uti, thyroid disease, and cushings disease. Im now on medication to help manage everything. I am finally feeling better now. Im going to need my medicine for the rest of my life though. I like to be the center of attention (meaning I dont care for other dogs), so I would need a home by myself or be able to be kept separated. I havent been around cats, but I can be tested with them. I am a very sweet little girl. Ive already been spayed. Im up to date on vaccinations, heartworm/lymes negative, flea treated, wormed, and microchipped. Im also crate trained. I do have occasional accidents but hopefully once the cushings is controlled that will get better. Please consider helping me out by fostering me or better yet giving me a forever home. Potential adopters need to realize that Olivia will need to remain on medication for the remainder of her life. This is a must! ** Applications will not be screened if they do not meet the listed requirements.**

animal.description:
Mr. Al Bino is a 2 year old cream doberman boy who came to us as a stray. He was really difficult to catch and it took them a couple weeks to get him. Due to this we do not recommend a home for him that ever has him off leash except in a fenced yard. He is good with female dogs but not male dogs. He needs to be an only dog or in a home with a female dog only. He loves to cuddle with his foster mom but he is a nervous nelly and he will circle and growl at his butt from time to time. He can be anxious at times but does relax. He does best with a routine and schedule where he knows what to expect when. We want the best for this boy and would prefer someone with doberman experience that understands not only male to male aggression but also the issues that can come along with him. 

The adoption fee for this handsome boy is $225. He has been neutered, microchipped and is up to date on vaccines!

Want to meet Mr. Al Bino? Submit an adoption application and someone will be in touch to schedule a meet n greet to see if hes the right match for you!

animal.description: On September 11th, 2015 Sonny was hit by a car in Chicago and taken to Chicago Animal Care and Control. He sat there for almost a week.....his euthanasia date was set but that didn't stop ICARe president Margaret from doing everything possible to save his life. After many, many phone calls and emails we got Sonny to safety and more importantly to see the vet! Tests were done showing a spinal cord injury that will not heal. Sonny had no use of his back legs. He also could not urinate on his own so his bladder had to be expressed manually. Let me tell you how amazing this dog is. He can now urinate on his own AND even more amazing is Sonny is getting therapy and regaining the function in his back legs. He can take several steps and stand on his own! Sonny has some wheels to help him get around on longer walks as his front end is very strong and he is perfectly capable of going all over! Sonny needs a special, special forever home. A family that will love him and treat him like a king.

animal.description:
Better With Older Children  /  Last weigh-in: 42 lbs

On April 25th, one of our rescue partners notified us of an abandoned puppy in need of medical attention. This tiny pup had been left behind by his family in an empty apartment for who knows how long with nothing but rat poison and antifreeze. After seeing this poor puppy coughing up blood, our rescue partners knew that he would require immediate medical attention and the help of a rescue if he were going to have any chance of survival, so they contacted us to see if we would be able to help. We knew we had to help, and he was immediately transported to AEC.

As we suspected, Cole has ingested rat poison, and based on his X-rays, he had also ingested something sharp. Cole required an immediate blood transfusion, and thanks to our Napoleons Hero's program, we have a list of Streetdogs (adoptable and alum) who have been blood type tested! And lucky for Cole, we had two healthy eligible dogs, #sdfDannyZuko and alum #sdfVanGogh, who mobilized to help their newest Streetdog family member!

Update 5/1: Cole has spent the past couple of days at Grace for further treatment and to monitor his vitals, and we are so happy to report that this sweet little boy is doing great! His platelet counts are up, and it appears that the sharp object previously seen on his x-ray has passed! Now that he is gaining weight with small, frequent meals, he's looking and feeling so much better! And today, he was even able to make a few new friends (dog and cat) and spend some time with his new dog friends outside in the yard! Cole will move to a medical foster soon, where he will continue to receive regular treatment and be closely monitored.

* Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
This is Cooper, a 3-year old male Pyr who is very people-friendly, house-trained and healthy. He walks very well on a leash and harness. Cooper is okay with cats and has played well with other dogs at the rescue.  

Although he is 3 years old, Cooper is still an adolescent and exhibits an adolescent's quirky  behavior. Cooper acts like a big cuddly goofball most of his day, but like most large breed dogs does not realize how big he is. Cooper is not your calm laid back Pyr!  Occasionally he may pick up an item not his own, so he does need some supervision.  
Cooper's other quirk is that is does not like trucks. As usual, there is a reason for his attitude, and his previous home had a fence in front of the house. Cooper at times overreacts to loud trucks. Cooper like most pyrs needs a fenced yard. His new owners must continue to work with him to keep him from back sliding.

If you would like more information about Cooper, or would like to schedule a time to meet him, please contact us at 920-293-8885 or wooflodge@yahoo.com. All of our dogs are current on vaccinations and are spayed or neutered.

Bombay Frankie is excited to meet people! Unless he is distracted by his environment (i.e. another dog), he wants to give people a big slobbery hello.

He has Medium energy. Loves to walk. But will also take a decent amount of time during the day to take a good snooze.

He is a very reactive/excitable dog with regards to other dogs. He is very curious to go meet other dogs, but in the very limited interactions he has had with other dogs, he seems to not have the best manners. Will try to snap at other dogs when trying to interact. He will need to be the only pet at home.

He is affectionate but not too needy. He is house trained! We are working on crate training and he is able to spend 3-4 hours in the crate throughout the day and he sleeps in the crate. Bombay Frankie can sit, paw, lay down, stay, come, and kennel.

Bombay Frankie would do well with an owner who has time to take him on long walks or some runs. Or in a home with a yard, he is able to run around in.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Due to Covid 19, no visits are allowed without an approved application. To apply for this dog, please go to www.adoggie4you.org. Please no phone calls. Adoption fee for this dog is $200. The dog is approximately 5 years old.

My name is Chula. I used to have a daddy that was a special friend to A Doggie 4 You, but one day he sat down in his chair and we couldn't wake him up. We kept trying for several days. We were very hungry and scared. It was really hot and we didn't know what to do. Finally we heard people trying to break in. We knew we had to protect daddy, so we wouldn't let them in. We did our best, but these men in uniforms came in and put a tight noose around our necks and dragged us away. We fought hard and were very scared, especially when we were thrown in a closed truck then a scary pen that was very noisy.

Finally a friend of our foster mom came to pick us up. We heard them trying to convince her to let them put us to sleep. But she said no and they loaded us up and took us to the ranch. We were really scared when we got there, even though we knew our foster mom. But we didn't trust anyone. It didn't take long for us to recognize we weren't in danger anymore. We still miss dad, but our foster mom is really nice and she says she misses dad too. The nice people here taught us how to walk on a leash, get in a kennel, and play with toys. We are really excited about finding a new family. I am sometimes a little shy around new people, but if you give me treats and are nice I warm up really fast. I love my brother Booger, but I wasn't around a lot of other dogs. I have made friends with some boy dogs I met. I would just have to get to know your other dog first. I don't like small dogs much, they are too noisy.
animal.name: Chula

animal.description:
FAST FACTS:
*6 Years Old - 55 Pounds
*Medium Energy: Can Be Playful But Also Loves to Lounge
*Good Walking Buddy
*Dog Friendly 
*No Cats
*Adult-Only Home (No Children)
*Potty/Crate Trained


BIO:
Hi there! My name is Moon Pie and I am a beautiful pittie/bulldog mix princess, estimated to be 6 years old and 55 pounds, who is available for adoption through Fetching Tails Foundation. I have a big personality that will keep you entertained: I am smart, funny (my piggy snorts and grunts will keep you laughing, for sure!), strong-willed and a social butterfly who loves to be around my people. I am generally laid-back and enjoy lounging around, but also have cute bursts of playful energy and would love a big toy box at my forever home so I can pick out the perfect prize with which to entertain myself. I would do best in a quieter home without kids or cats. I get along with other dogs - I can be barky when I first meet new friends (I just like to talk, what can I say?)  My favorite activities include going for long walks, playing with toys (I love squeaky ones!), sunbathing on the deck in our yard, and watching the world from my comfy dog bed by the windows or the couch.

I have pretty lovely manners, as well. I’m potty trained, and as a proper lady I prefer the privacy of my own yard when I need to poop. I am crate trained, as well, though I don't really need to be because I will find my favorite spot on the couch and nap until you return. When on adventures outside of the home, I am good (though a little strong) on a leash and am well-behaved during car rides since I love to look out the window as the world passes by! I am a sweet, sassy doll who would do great with a human who wants an exercise buddy for long walks (I can go about a mile a day with my foster momma!) as well as a loving, devoted companion for quiet nights at home. What are you waiting for? You know you wanna fill out that adoption application!

Love,
Moon Pie

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess. If any questions please email us!

Playful, social, and good-natured, he's a happy young dog who enjoys playing with other dogs.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

Her adopter should be a leader who can continue her training with rules, structure and boundaries.

She can hold a mean duration place for hours!

She is crate trained, house broken, spayed, micro chipped and up to date on vaccinations.

Chelsea comes with lifetime support from our good friends at Allied Dog Training. How awesome is that? Help is a call or text away.

Adopters must be willing to come to the Farm in Southern Dutchess County NY for handling lessons 2-3 times to take handling lessons to uphold her training. 

Not only are you adopting a fully trained dog- you receive help when needed- all questions answered promptly.

We care and back every dog that comes through our doors- for life.

She is well trained, super compliant and now needs a home to call her own.

While Chelsea is good with kids we prefer an adult only pet free home.  She can be over aroused with toys.  

Applications:

www.townandcountryk9resq.org

under contact us.

On his wish list is a home where he can sprint, maneuver and corner to fetch a tennis ball or even a large Jolly ball, with the reward of a good chomping afterward, his absolute favorite pastime. Adjustable, yes, hes just as happy hanging out quietly with his people indoors with his good manners, hes perfectly housetrained and can manage alone for a few hours while his people are out. We think he tends to like being an only child, or perhaps living with a single lady dog. Meet and greets can be accommodated with advance scheduling. Sorry, felines, youre not his type! animal.description:
1. What is your name?
Hi! My name is Fetty Wap!

2. How old are you?
I am around 2 years old.

3. What do you look like?
I have been told more than once that I look like Scooby Do! I am not really sure what that means, but Scooby must be one good-looking dude! I am a nice medium-sized red boy with the coolest stand-up ears you have ever seen. I have absolutely no poker face because my ears give me away every time. My eyes are sincere, almost doe-like and I am ALWAYS SMILING. I have a hilarious underbite and my lip often gets caught on my toof which makes for a comical resting face.

4. What do you like to eat?
Food, duh! I love food, I love peanut butter, I love treats, I love bananas, I love anything you offer me. I used to get in trouble because I thought I should put my mouth on everything and everything belonged in my mouth, but, not anymore! I know better now!

5. What kind of personality do you have?
HAPPY. I am always happy. ALWAYS. I am so silly, I love to goof off! I have a bunch of energy, I will do anything you ask of me and I promise to give it my all no matter what you want me to try. I am friendly to everyone I meet. I love meeting new people. I have a TON of toy drive, tug drive and a will to work. I am looking for someone to adventure with, let’s go places, let’s try new things, let’s play, you name it, I am game. I just want to be your friend. My foster parents are so proud of me because I used to not really have any interest in people, I did such a good job entertaining myself that I didn’t think people were important. But now I have seen the light, people are everything! I will love you so hard if you allow it! I am generally a very confident boy, the only time I am a little unsure is in high stress environments that are new to me, but my foster parents take me everywhere and work with me on that so I am improving every day. I can be a softie if someone is harsh to me, but I am not a scaredy cat, I have endless amounts of curiosity that keeps me motivated to explore and try things out.

6. Describe your perfect day
Every day is a perfect day, so this is a hard one. Instead let’s list things I love to do. I love to go on walks, I need my walks and I make them so much fun, you will love them just as much as I do. Wait until I show you how fun it is to roll in bushes and landscaping. Also, we can do parkour! I love to “climb” onto rocks, picnic benches, playground equipment, you name it. Just point and say climb and I will try it! At home I love to chew, I can chew for hours and my foster family has it all figured out, as long as I have some of my favorite chew toy options available, I will self-entertain and stay out of trouble for hours while they watch tv or cook dinner. I love to play tug and I love to play fetch! I love to play with my small group of dog foster siblings too. Oh, and I love to train! This nice man that I live with taught me all of these things and we practice all the time, well, at least I try to get him to practice with me all of the time. My favorite part of training is when he says FREE and I get to run into his arms and get rewarded. I also love to swim! This past summer my foster mom taught me to dock dive, I am not the best at it, but I still LOVE to try! I have no fear and I know that with more practice my jumping will get much better! We have jumped at both regular swimming pools and official dog diving pools. We also LOVE to go swim in rivers and creeks, we call it “going creeking” it is so much fun!

7. What is your favorite toy?
I have a favorite indestructible chew called a goughnut and I spend hours with it every day. Even the strongest goughnut only lasts so long though, I can chew better than most. I also love moose antlers, bully sticks and frozen raw marrow bones too! I like to play fetch with the ChuckIt! Rubber balls and I also love to catch and retrieve frisbee rollers. Whoever adopts me will be supplied with all of these items so that I have the best transition possible!

8. Do you know any tricks?
Yes! I sit and hold my sit very nicely until you say free! I know down, climb, come and heel as well! In addition to that I have learned to fetch. My best trick to offer though is comedic relief. I am so good at making everyone laugh. I am a weirdo and I encourage you to embrace it. These are hard times and I promise you that with me around you won’t be able to feel down, I will keep you up and smiling always!

9.  What scares you?
Not much, and to most people I look completely and utterly fearless. I have been with my foster parents for a long time so they know me really well and they say that I am a little nervous in new environments, but the only way they can tell is that I am not quite as responsive to my commands as I am at home.

11. Do you have any doggie best friends?
I have a lot of dog friends! I LOVE my foster siblings, my favorite is a Dutch Shepherd named Iya. We love to wrestle! I am very playful with dogs that I know, but because of my genetics and background my foster parents are very protective of me and they only let me play with dogs that they know would be a good match for my antics. I do have a couple of very bossy female dog siblings in my house and when I get too silly or rough they really let me have it and I listen because they mean it! I have a lot of respect for them. Dogs seem to really like me, I am a likable dude.

12. If you could be anywhere in the world, where would it be?
That is a toss-up, I would either be in my living room to chew and play with my toys next to my people or on a walk with my people.

13. How is your health?
My health is great now! When I came in I had some health problems, I had a horrible recurring UTI that wouldn’t go away, but we finally kicked it to the curb a few months ago and it never came back! Because of the poor conditions I was held in for my first few years of life I have very flat feet and splayed toes with some supination in my pasterns. My foster mom has fed me very nutritional diet and has walked me on grass, sand, gravel, hills and stairs daily since I was rescued and we have made some improvement. My flat feet don’t stop me or even slow me down at all, I can still do everything normal, I will just never be a show dog or a foot model ? 


14. How long have you lived in your foster home?
I have been with my foster family since February 2020. My foster parents were dedicated to giving me all of the time and training I needed before placing me for adoption, we all agree that I am now totally ready for a family of my own! 

15. Who do you live with in your foster home and who is your closest            companion? 
I live with my foster parents (my foster dad is a trainer) and their 2 human children (6 and 8 years old). I have lots of foster brother and sister dogs, it’s always a full house here.

16. Where do you hang out when you are home alone?
When my foster parents are not home, I am in my crate. I am perfectly crate trained and I do great at relaxing in my crate. I also sleep in my crate every night. I am quiet and sleep through the night with no issue!

18. What do you love about your foster family?
I love that they love me and aren’t in a rush to push me out. They put their all into me and they are 100% dedicated in finding me the perfect home. They taught me how to dog, I really had no idea what I was or what I should do when I was rescued, I was lost and needed a lot of direction.

19. What was life like before you were rescued by Even Chance and         brought into the welcoming arms of your foster parents?
I was rescued by the ASPCA from a NY dogfighting raid. I was one of about 30 dogs that were confiscated. I was raised in a small box in a NY basement, I really had no idea about any of the world outside of that basement. The ASPCA got me to a temporary shelter but soon reached out to Even Chance because they realized I needed some special attention and training. 


Closing lines: Even Chance does not operate on a first come, first serve basis. In most cases we have already decided the type of home and owner we want for our dogs. These opinions are based on the temperament tests we perform prior to accepting the dog into our program and the behaviors the dogs display as they spend time in our homes. Our agency reserves the right to deny acceptance of any dog to an owner who we feel the lifestyle does not match that of the dog. We are in no way judging you or your lifestyle; we simply want to put our dogs in the best living situation possible. We take very seriously the decision we make when it comes to placing one of our dogs in a forever home. If I sound like the perfect pit bull for your and your family and you are interested in giving me a forever home, do not hesitate! Please fill out an application here and my foster family will contact you to schedule an in-person meet and greet. We look forward to meeting any and all interested applicants.

animal.description:
JoJo came out of Miami-Dade Animal Services and needed immediate medical attention.
She had a severe head tilt and couldn’t even walk in a straight line. She had several growths/tumors needing removed, needed Spay and a dental.
Also, needed to be seen by the eye dr.
So we did the following on her to make her a beautiful happy healthy dog.
Bloodwork, Thyroid Test, Urinalysis, Spay, Dental , Removal of Growths, Vaccines,Dewormed, Microcipped, we took her to the Neurologist to address the head tilt. She was put on antibiotics .( cleared up)
We took her to the eye dr and it was determined she has slight dry eye so a drop of Tachrolimus must be put in both eyes daily.
EVERYTHING was addressed by us as obviously she was let down by her past owners.
It is so hard to believe that this absolute sweetheart of a dog who is great with people , kids and other dogs was so let down in this world.

She comes with one month Free Pet Insurance by Trupanion.
Also, a go home Goodie bag includes: grain free food, treats, toys, bowls, toys, shampoo, lead , collar, measuring cup,etc
There is an application process, we call you Veterinarians ( you must have 5 years of previous history of caring for a pet) and a home check.
ONLY Broward & Palm Bch Counties can apply at this time.
Please, call us for more info or for an application. 954-588-7045

animal.description:
This beautiful girl is a Belgian Malinois.   Arrow is the total package of beauty and brains.  She is about 15 months old and a very active, playful and loving dog.
Arrow lives with three other dogs in her current foster home.  She loves to play, and would prefer to live with a large, active male dog(s) in her permanent home.
If you are not familiar with the Belgian Malinois breed, please take time to educate yourself :
 https://www.woofproject.org/malinois-breed

They are fantastic dogs but not for everyone and not for the novice dog owner.
More specifically, for Arrow:
• NO apartments, condos, townhomes or shared living situations
• A six foot fence is REQUIRED.  Malinois are known for scaling or jumping fences – they are great athletes
• You must lead an active lifestyle.  She gets 5+ miles of walking daily in her foster home plus lots of play time daily with her canine companions
• She loves to play ball and frisbee
• This is not a dog who will be happy being at home by herself during the day.  She would be better with someone who works from home or can take her to work with them.
• Her house manners are impeccable.  She is housebroken and has never chewed inappropriately.  She does prefer to be allowed on the couch and human bed, but will stay off if you insist.
• We are recommending a home with NO kids and NO small animals.  She lives with older kids in her current foster home and that might be a possibility.
• She would be fantastic for an adopter interested in competitive canine sports or obedience.  She is super smart, easy to train, and a phenomenal athlete.  These are all characteristics of the breed.  The breed does demand training, and experienced handlers.  
• Experienced homes only please.  It is a requirement that you have experience owning a guarding or working breed canine.
• Arrow showed some signs of anxiety when she first arrived in her foster home, but settled in in a matter of days.   Her current foster family will work with her permanent family to transition her to her new home gradually and set her up for success.
This is a very special girl who will steal your heart.  Are you the right forever home for her?
 

If you would like to adopt Arrow, please visit our website and apply today!

https://www.washingtongsd.org/adopt

Please note that we do require a secure fenced yard.

Our hours are by appointment only. IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH YOU WILL BE CONTACTED typically within 72 hours. YOU WILL HEAR FROM US ONLY IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH FOR ONE OF OUR FOSTERS AND OUR ADOPTION GUIDELINES/PROGRAM. WE MUST REVIEW A COMPLETED APPLICATION BEFORE A POSSIBLE APPOINTMENT IS ARRANGED. NO EXCEPTIONS. All visits with the puppies/dogs are by approved applications and appointments only.

*************** We reserve the right to refuse any adoption without justification and not all applications or inquiries may receive a response. ***************

animal.description:
Meet Xolo...
A 5 year old blue Doberman.
49 lbs and gaining back his weight.
Xolo is very people social, walks well on a leash. 
Xolo does well with smaller younger pups but not too fond of dogs larger than him.
Crate trained, house trained.
Xolo loves playing with toys and giving lots of kisses.
Xolo is neutered, microchipped and Up to Date  on his vaccines.
Xolo is negative for all tick diseases but tested positive for heartworm. 
Xolo is currently being treated with a slow kill type treatment and he is doing well.
Xolo looks hairless but this is a common trait with blue Dobermans. With time and good nutrition we hope that his beautiful blue coat will return again.
This boy is looking for a lifelong home of his own.
He has not been cat tested but would prefer a home without small animals.


Forgotten Friends Texas Rescue RGV is located in Mission, Texas.

Forgotten Friends does not have a shelter - Our dogs are raised in foster homes by local caring, loving families. Each dog comes spayed or neutered, up-to-date with age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm tested and are current with monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives.

For out of area adoptions, the fee is $400 for adult dogs and $500 for puppies 6 months and under.

animal.description: As a big, black, and fearful dog, Ace has some odds stacked against him. But luckily for him, he also has a big team of people working with him to become more confident, and to show him that we are there to help him and to love him. With proper intros, Ace is making friends left and right! If you are wondering, proper intros for Ace means no direct eye contact, speaking softly, offering treats, and letting him approach you. It can take some time for that tail to become untucked and that's okay. You can't rush this kind of thing. You know when you have Ace's seal of approval because he will show you his naughty side! We diligently redirect him and he is learning quickly what kind of behavior gets rewarded. And who doesn't love rewards?! You may also get some nibbly kisses once he really feels comfortable with you. According to his surrender notes, Ace is house trained, crate trained, and has lived with another dog. He is afraid of lawn mowers but loves car rides, squeaky toys, and tug of war. His notes also say, He barks when he sees someone. Then hides. He watches them for a little bit and then loves them. We love you, too, Ace. So much. I weigh approximately 69 lbs. Click here to view my paperwork.

Hello! My name is Waylon and I am looking for a fetch partner. I like to play fetch. And I love toys. Squeaky toys are the best. Do you have toys? I really like toys. I will show you how to play fetch with them too. Did I mention I like to play fetch?

Anyway, Im a five year old country boy that likes to do hound things. My foster mom says Im too smart for my britches but thats just silly because I dont have any britches. I like to keep busy so I could use a home that understands my hound ways. Im a talker too and though my foster mom says hound people like talkers, maybe your neighbors wont so probably a country home would be best for me. I like to take off after critter so Im not looking to live with cats. Im an independent chill kind of guy, although I'd like to be the only dog in your home. Even though the rescue ladies swoon over me as I am, I am slimming down now that I am taking thyroid medicine, which I will have to take for the rest of my life. Im an indoor dog and have good house manners but I can get carried away and jump around when I see a toy so I may be too much for small kids. I got a hounds heart of gold and would love to be your best friend and play fetch. I'll even teach you like I taught my foster mom. Did I mention I like to play fetch? And toys. Im crazy about toys.

You can learn more about me and apply to adopt me at www.rescuedohio.org.

animal.description:
Cadette is about 1 - 1 ½ years old.  He came to Just Cause Rescue when he was found injured in Biloxi with wounds and a broken leg that had healed on its own.
-In his foster home Cadette has loved to be around other dogs, he can play a little rough with small dogs but with guidance that should get better.  He is just happy to be in a home!
-Kennel trained, he enjoys his kennel for security since he can be kind of shy at first.
-House training is going well, he is having fewer and fewer accidents.
-Loves treats so he will learn commands quickly since he is food motivated.  He will let you pet him and take his food bowl so no food aggression with his foster people.
-While he is shy he is opening up quickly and now enjoys kisses on his head!
-Cadette walks great on a leash and is learning that going in the house is fun, we really believe he lived outside his whole life.
-He is still a young guy that needs to play to burn off his energy and be worked with commands, he will nibble your toes but he is learning they aren’t toys!
-While we do not know what this young guys past was like, we do know he is a happy guy so thankful to be off the streets and being taught what it is like to be a spoiled dog now!

German Shepherd
Female, 7 years old, 75 pounds

Ceto is enthusiastic and interested in everything! She loves treats and even knows some commands. When we met her at the shelter, she didn't even bark for attention. She was a good, quiet little lady. Patiently awaiting her ticket out of the shelter. She is a total leaner and loves to put her head on your lap for pets. She is a superstar! She adores people and bonds quickly to them. While she is great with people, she needs a home where she is the only dog. 

Ceto does have hip dysplasia and her weak backend means she is unable to jump and should avoid stairs. She is looking for a home without stairs and would prefer less strenuous hikes. She can do daily walks but is limited and does need help getting into a car. 

She does like toys like balls, loving to chew and rip them apart. She also loves to hide bones but doesn't dig in the yard. She may get into trash cans and her favorite spot is on the couch. 

Ceto follows people around and is oh so sweet. She demands pets and doesn't like when you stop. She cannot receive enough love. 

She came to us from Salinas Animal Services.

animal.description:
Please give Mr. Herry the chance he deserves.  He has had a pretty traumatic life so far.  We've been told he was chained up in the back yard prior to coming to the shelter.  He had little to no trust in humans when arriving at the shelter.  Once we pulled him from the shelter we sought out some professional training for him.  The training went well; however, he had a little setback when transported to Oregon.  He has since bonded tremendously with his foster and loves to play with other foster dogs.  We are not sure how seamless his transition to a forever home will be but we intend on being a part of that transition as needed.  He will require lots of patience and understanding of what he has been through.  He will need a relatively quiet environment.  May even do best with a single owner home.  He does not like raised voices or fast moving arms in a motion of swinging at or near him.  He is a super sweet boy once he starts to trust his human.  Seeks out pets and love.  Even a bit playful when he is relaxed.  Please don't let his past influence what his future can be.  He truly is a good boy with a bad start.  He is neutered, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. 

Please contact us if you are interested in adopting, or even fostering, one of our dogs. We are a federal non-profit rescue. We do require a completed application and a home visit prior to adopting. Please go to our website at www.theheartofrescue.org to complete an application or call 541-782-THOR (8467).

animal.description:
DOB: 11/13/16

Sweet Hannah spent the first 6 months of her life living in a back yard with her 5 siblings where they never got to experience the warmth of a humans touch. From there she was taken in by a wonderful rescue but unfortunately, with their limited resources she and her siblings still rarely experienced human interactions. Hannah came to ROAR back in January with her friend Judd and has been with us ever since. She has made progress since arriving, however, she still has a long journey ahead of her. She needs someone who has the patience, experience, dedication, and determination to teach this sweet girl that the world and people are safe. Since Hannah is so fearful of the world around her she would do best in a quiet and calm environment. Hannah also requires another dog in the home to show her the ropes as well as a fenced in yard.


Hannah is up to date on vaccinations, is micro-chipped, and is spayed. 
Adoption fee is $350.

If you are interested in learning more about miss Hannah please email the Adoption Coordinator at adopt.roar@gmail.com or call the shelter at 203-438-0158

**For more information regarding ROAR’s adoption policies and procedures, please visit our website at roar-ridgefield.org and select the ‘adopt’ tab on the home page. ROAR does not accept online applications. All applications must be filled out at the shelter.

animal.description:
This handsome guy is about 1.5 years old, 58 lbs and came to us as a stray. It’s clear that Robbie was not socialized properly as a pup. He gets very overstimulated when meeting people for the first time and can be a bit intimidating while doing so. Once you get past the initial meeting and he learns you are safe, Robbie is such a wonderful dog. He loves to run and play and get pets! He is a fence fighter, another sign of over-stimulation - meaning he tends to run up and down the fence or other boundary marker barking at passers by. He would do best in a calm, Chow savvy home with structure, continued training, consistency, and no children. Robbie is being fostered about a half hour north of Houston.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application @ https://form.jotform.us/41173109602142. Once approved, home visit and reference checks are also required.

If you have further questions outside of this listing, please email chowmail.hccc@gmail.com.

animal.description: Slater will be arriving at his Mississippi foster home tomorrow and we can't wait to see him blossom! Thanks to Changing 42 Animal Rescue, he is looking and feeling much better than he was when he was first found as a stray in Alabama. He is incredibly shy but very sweet and will gently nudge you for attention. He is good with other dogs. Slater still needs some routine vetting and needs to be neutered so he will not be available for adoption for a couple of weeks. We would also like to get to know him a little better, as well. Please check back for updates on this beautiful boy!!UPDATE 5/8: Slater is doing fabulous in his Mississippi foster home. He saw the vet and is scheduled to be neutered on Monday. He did test very low heartworm positive so he started on preventative and medications and will be retested soon. He loves his skin foster brother and mom but he seems to be very frightened of men. He also seems to have some discomfort when walking and wearing a collar but does great with a harness on, likely due to the injury/sores on his neck that are freshly healed.7/30 UPDATE: Slater was retested for heartworm disease and retested as very light positive. We have decided to continue with medications for slow-kill treatment and he will need to be retested in a few months.

animal.description:
Parker is such a handsome boy. He is around 3 years old. He does great on a leash and likes to get outside for walks. He even more loves to have a big fenced in property of some kind. That is what we are looking for for this big boy. He does well with other dogs and loves to run with them. It is a no go for cats. We put no kids but as long as they are older and understand he wants his space (he is not one to be hugged or overly loved on). He likes his pets and that is about it. He is a high strung, busy dog that would love a big yard or farm to be as active as he wants to be. PLEASE READ BELOW FOR UPDATES.

PUPDATE 6/1/20 - Parker went to a home for about a week and it was very clear that he was meant to be an outside dog. He just loves to be outside and would love to be on a farm. He would need a fenced in area or an electric fence, because who doesn't love to follow smells? Otherwise, he is a wonderful companion. He would just prefer to be working and busy.  He won't be a cuddly house dog.

PUPDATE 8/8/2020 - Parker is being removed from PetFinder to take some time to work with his anxiety.

PUPDATE 11/5/20 - Parker has been being exercised more and also started some anti-anxiety medication for the past few months. He is doing wonderful now that we have figured out his dose. This is something that he would need to continue to stay on daily and your vet can order it through your pharmacy. It is only around $25 a month.

Sierra is an 2 year old German Shepherd mixed Dog. She came to us from a high kill shelter in Houston.  She is fully vetted, microchipped, and spayed. 

Sierra is an amazing, young, sweet girl with much energy.  She will do best with an owner who has experience with GSDs and in positive dog training.  She will need an family who has time to teach her and the patience to give her as she learns what it is like to be part of their pack. Sierra has an old fracture in her right femoral bone that has healed and she is well-compensated with this. An interested, approved adopter can speak with our vet about this. 

You must be approved to adopt through our group before meeting any of our adoptable dogs. Please note that this is a volunteer based group and NOT a SHELTER. Puppies are in foster homes. https://www.facebook.com/pg/forgottendogsrescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=3076201985731911

Hello Mello!  We are excited to let everyone know that Mello is officially up for adoption!  Mello came to us in February and required immediate spinal surgery to fix a herniated disc but is all healed up and doing great!  He is a master of the naps!  Mello truly lives up to his name; he is one chill dude.  He would, if he could, cuddle and get belly rubs all day.  Sounds like a pretty good day, right?  Mello has exhibited some separation anxiety, so he would do best in a home where someone is with him most of the time.  He loves car rides so would be happy running some errands in between belly rub sessions.  In addition, while we have been working on his confidence around other dogs, we think he would do best in a home without other animals.  He has gone from being reactive around other dogs to being able to be walked on leash by them without much of a reaction but, this work will need to be continued so he is able to gain more confidence and be a good boy around potential dog friends.  He is a smart kid and knows sit, down, place, stay and wait.  Smarty pants!  He has spent some time being crate trained, too, but he isn’t super keen on it and would prefer to not have to spend a lot of time in it and, if used, will need additional training to be comfortable.  In general, Mello has come a long way with us but, will need someone who is willing to continue to work with him, help him build confidence and be his forever snuggle buddy.  He loves to play fetch and rolling around in the grass so we think a yard would be pretty awesome for him.  He also loves kids!  And, his favorite game is hide and seek. Adorable!  
 
If you are up for belly rubs, snuggles and hide and seek, please fill out an application which can be found at our website, www.forgottendogsrescue.com. We estimate Mello was born around 2012, so he's an older guy,  and weighs about 70 pounds.  Mello’s adoption fee is $350 and he is neutered, microchipped and up to date on appropriate vaccines.

Tripp and his brother Clark are searching for a home together, as they have never successfully lived apart. The rescue has tried to find them individual homes but it has never worked out. They need a canine companion, preferably each other, and someone that is home 99% of the time.

They were adopted as pups into a home with a stay at home mom and had a fenced yard so they were not leash trained. They had each other and never had to be crated. Well time passed, and family dynamics changed and resulted in a move. The new residence could not accommodate the boys so they came into the rescue. They have so much love to give to a family looking for companionship.  He has been described as the perfect dog by a family that did a trial adoption but was unable to be home enough to meet his needs.  He is completely vetted and his adoption fee is $200

animal.description:
Reaction to New People: Cautious
Meet Betty..

Betty is a very special girl. She came into rescue with significant trauma to her eyes and head, she was depressed, terrified and clearly endured abuse.

We couldn't save Betty's eyes but we have done everything we can to repair her heart and teach her that the world isn't such a bad place and not every human is cruel. She's come leaps and bounds with her rehab and shes ready to find a foster home to continue to learn and grow.

Betty is crate trained, its her safe place. She enjoys going on walks but is a slow walker and reactive to other dogs on walks. She LOVES to roll in the grass, its her favorite! Betty needs to be the only pet in the home because of her past trauma and she deserves to be the queen of the castle. She does not prefer small children, or men. A man can live in the home but she needs to have her main handler be female, we do however believe over time she will warm up to a kind man. Betty is in general low matinence once she learns the ;layout of the home. 

She loves to cuddle and play, she loves treats and has just discovered toys are awesome! Whoever wins this girl over will have the most loyal friend anyone could have. 

If interested in our special girl, please submit an application.
www.animalhelpalliance.org

animal.description:
Finley is a 10 yeas old male, 12 pounds.

You would think with all this boy has been through that he would have an attitude, but he is just the sweetest most full of kisses boy around.

Finley was rescued from a local shelter, he was unable to use his hind end. We scooped him up and off to the neurologist who said it was orthopedic.... off to the specialty surgeon. Surgeon finds that he has a dislocation in his pelvis, an old fracture that cannot be repaired, the leg had to come off (to relieve pain)... then it is found that he also has IVDD... so the disc is also repaired. Because both injuries were old, he has not regained full use of the one back leg so he has a cart that he LOVES!

Because of his condition, Finley does need to be expressed to go potty. Finley doesn't want to let this scare you off - It is SUPER easy to learn which means I go potty on your schedule! Check out our very own Dr. Wong at Southeast Veterinary Neurology, who did my surgery, teach you how to express a dog!

We have medically done all we can for this happy boy. No pain and all parts working as well as they can making a super sweet little boy who is easy to take care of, get along with dogs and kids, and a

ll he needs now is a family of his own.

If you are interested in adopting me, please complete the DRSF Online Adoption form.My adoption fee covers all my (prior) vet care (adopter receives vet records). For more information refer to the DRSF Adoption Fee page.If you have any questions about adoption or want more info, you can email: info@dachshundrescuesouthflorida.com

animal.description:
Ozzy is a 5 year old 13 pound male chiweenie

He is a sweet sweet boy, and earned his name as his transporter was listening to some classic rock on the way to Miami, Ozzy was singing along, and his transporter decided he was "barking at the moon" and thus he had his new name!

Ozzy was brought to a local shelter back at the beginning of July, his owners brought him there to be euthanized because he was paralyzed in his hind end. The shelter asked for help and here he is! Ozzy gets around great with and without his amazing cart and does need to be expressed, but that's super easy to learn.

Because of his injury, Ozzy does need to be expressed to go potty. He doesn't want to let this scare you off - It is SUPER easy to learn which means he goes potty on your schedule- no sniffing around or waiting! Check out our very own Dr. Wong at Southeast Veterinary Neurology, who examined me, teach you how to express a dog!

From Ozzy:

I am Sir Speedy, and I've got a great set of wheels! My foster mom will tell you that I'm always on the go and up for a run around the yard, a romp with my dog friends (my current companions are cart drivers just like me) or a nice, long stroll around the neighborhood. Once I get to know you, I will shower you with kisses. I do like to use my voice, so expect to hear me announce visitors and bark when meeting new friends-be they human or canine. Best feature? Well, just look at my photo. As my foster mom says, "One look at those perky ears, and you can't help but fall in love!"

If you are interested in adopting me, please complete the DRSF Online Adoption form.My adoption fee covers all my (prior) vet care (adopter receives vet records). For more information refer to the DRSF Adoption Fee page.If you have any questions about adoption or want more info, you can email: info@dachshundrescuesouthflorida.com

animal.description:
Marina is a 10 year old female, who is 16 pounds.

Marina has made an incredible transformation in her spirit since coming to DRSF. She was a stray at a shelter way outside our area, and her sad face tugged at our hearts and we could not leave here there to be euthanized, and so we arranged transport to South Florida where our community provided the care that she needed to start her life over. You can see more photos and all the love that came to Marina on her Fundrazr.

After all her medical treatment, Marina was left with only teeth (all the others had to be removed due to neglect), but that does not slow her or her appetite down!

Since being in foster care, Marina has become so much more confident, and her sweet, funny personality has come out with the help of people who love her.

animal.description:
Hansel is a 10 year old 11 pound boy who is soooo sweet!!

He had back surgery a couple of years ago, but he is still unable to walk very far. He can get up and take a few steps and he can go to the bathroom himself with only occasional assistance. He asks to go outside and if he can't get there, he goes on a pee pad.

He's good with kids, adults and other dogs. He LOVES toys and snuggling near people (head on feet if at all possible).
He's a super sweet boy who needs very little extra care.

Hansel:

I'm a master blanket burrower! Although my back legs don't work, I can climb into bed and wiggle myself under the covers so that I am fully covered with just the tip of my snout sticking out. My sniffer monitors my surroundings; I can detect a duck outside and give him the barking business without ever leaving the comfort of my bed.

You need not feel sorry for this IVDD survivor; I can outrun my housemates when the food bowl comes out! Speaking of suppertime, it's a good idea to feed me separately. I'm such a foodie, I tend to get testy when I sense competition. You should know that I am rather vocal; I'll bark when someone is at the door, when meeting new dogs and people (although I like everyone I meet) and, of course, when I see/smell those ducks!

If you are interested in adopting me, please complete the DRSF Online Adoption form.My adoption fee covers all my (prior) vet care (adopter receives vet records). For more information refer to the DRSF Adoption Fee page.If you have any questions about adoption or want more info, you can email: info@dachshundrescuesouthflorida.com

animal.description: Meet Donald, a Pit Bull Terrier. He is he sweetest boy. He is a big baby and loves other dogs and all people! He is a shelter favorite! Donald is somewhat of a special needs pup. When Donald came into the shelter he was not walking normal. We took Donald to the vet and found out he has luxating patellas (meaning his knee's pop in and out). Most dogs will go their life without needing surgical intervention. Because Donald is young, our vet recommended keeping him on joint supplements. Please consider giving this sweet pup the home he truly deserves. Donald is neutered, heartworm negative, microchipped, dewormed, vaccinated and flea treated. Donald's adoption fee is $200. Please visit our website www.ohiospca.org to fill out an application on Donald. Please note on the application his name. Thank you!

animal.description: Chucho is the king of bite-sized energy scattered throughout your day. A little bit of fetch here, a little bit of running around the yard there, and a whole lot of cuddling up in between makes every day with Chucho just as great as the last! This handsome boy is exactly what you need to brighten up your home with a big pitty grin. Chucho loves to play in the backyard, rolling around in the grass and people watching from afar. Even inside Chucho loves to play around with his toys, shaking them everywhere and enjoying a bit of catch with his treats. Chucho has learned it's just as important to enjoy the downtime as well. He's a world-class cuddler who's sure to let you know when it's time for some attention with cute noises and endless excitement. And if you're still asleep? He's sure to nuzzle up to you for some belly rubs. Chucho is sure to be a bright spot in any home but would do best in a semi-active family with a backyard. Due to a minor leg limp, he'll require a bit of extra care so as not to aggravate it by enjoying too much playtime. But you'll easily forget when you see his sweet brown eyes and trademark big grin in your day! Come see this handsome boy today!

animal.description: ROCKY is a male Lab/Boxer about 4 1/2 years old. Rocky is a happy guy with energy to spare! He would be best suited for an active person who will include him in lots of activities, walks and play time. Rocky loves the kiddie pool and water from the hose in the warm weather and loves the snow in the winter too! He does, however, not like the cold! :) He will snuggle all up in his warm blankets and chew on his favorite treat - a Greenie - when he comes in from the cold outside ! Rocky also wears a coat now that the really cold weather has come. (see above - what a handsome guy!!) We recommend no young children, as Rocky would be too active for them and can get overly enthusiastic when running and playing. He also has a tendency to sometimes pull on/grab the leash. He will need someone who can work on/with this. Training is recommended, but Rocky will learn quickly. He is a smart boy! Using a martingale collar and easy-walk harness makes walking him much easier and much more enjoyable for both of you. An apartment would not be suitable - Rocky is looking for a home with a fenced yard where he can run and play! Rocky would prefer a home with no cats and would be happiest as the only dog in the home
animal.name: ROCKY

animal.description:
Local adoptions only: within a 75-mile radius of Quail Valley/Menifee, Southwest Riverside County.  Please note: L.A. and Orange Counties are out of area due to traffic/drive time.
Free at last, male Rogue and female Monroe were rescued from living in a small outdoor kennel together since they were puppies (approximately 7 years!). They've been at the rescue about 6 months and they are now about 8 years old. Rogue is a Mastiff/Pitbull Mix who is mostly black with a little white on chest and weighs about 77 pounds. Black/white Pitbull mix Monroe weighs 55 pounds. They only had each other for a long time and are very attached to each other.  They are looking for a good home together where they will be part of the family. Rogue is very sweet, cute and puppy-like.  Rogue is a very likable, good boy and knows to shake his paw.   Monroe is a happy, active, inquisitive, playful dog who is very sweet and loving. Rogue and Monroe have good temperaments and look and act young. They know to sit for food and treats.  They're friendly and good on a leash on walks and in public. They are house and crate trained. Considering their past, they are very nice dogs who are starved for attention, just want to be loved and be with their family. Also due to their past, they are a bit undersocialized with other dogs and will need proper introductions with other dogs. We recommend their new potential adopter be an experienced dog owner who has experience with this type of dog. Their new home should have a secure fenced yard and no small dogs or cats in the household.  Rogue and Monroe are healthy and have been spayed/neutered, vaccinated, dewormed and microchipped. They are ready and waiting to go to their new loving home.

$150 adoption fee for both, cash only, which is to help reimburse for a portion of expenses of dog rescue and rehabilitation. Adoption contract required. We deliver adopted pets to their new home to see where they will be living. 

$150 adoption fee for both, cash only, which is to help reimburse for a portion of expenses of dog rescue and rehabilitation. Adoption contract required. We are looking for adopters who are willing and able to care for this dog for its lifetime (10+ years). Location: Quail Valley/Menifee, Southwest Riverside County. Local adoptions only; within 75 mile radius because we deliver animal to its new home to do a home/yard check. Please note: L.A. and Orange Counties are out of area because of traffic and difficult, time-consuming drive.) We prescreen potential adopters before setting up a meeting.
.
If interested in this dog, please tell us a little about you, your family, your lifestyle, your other pets, your experience as a dog owner (which breed, etc.), where you live (which city in a home or apt) and what you are looking for in a dog. Thank you.

Our adoption process involves meeting the animal by appointment.We have the best interest of the animal in mind and our goal is to find a good, permanent home for each of our rescued animals.  We have the right to decline an application if we feel it is not a good match/fit or suitable home. If you like the animal and we both feel it is a good match, an application and adoption contract is completed.  A convenient day/time is arranged for us to deliver the animal to its new home to do a home/yard check (to make sure the home and yard is safe and secure). We will collect the adoption fee (cash only) when we deliver the animal to its new home.  All our adoptions are on a trial basis because our goal is to have a successful adoption where the animal has a good permanent home and never ends up in a bad situation again.  We ask that you give the animal a chance to adjust and settle in his new home and environment.  Going to a new home with new people and a new environment is traumatic and stressful.  It will take time for the animal to become comfortable around you and his/her new home. This should be a bonding period where you get to know the animal and connect with it, spend time with it and take things slow.  He/she will need to get to know and trust you and learn the rules of the house and what is expected of him/her. This takes time, sometimes 2-3 weeks.  During this time we will hold the adoption fee and if the adoption is not working out, we ask that you contact us and return the animal and we will refund your adoption fee.
animal.name: Rogue

animal.description: Kane is going to need a strong handler and someone that is going to keep up with his training. He is currently in training and he is doing so well!  Kane loves going on hikes and would make a great companion for someone who will travel with him often! Plus, he loves car rides and does amazing in the car! He is a goof ball, and loves to put on a big ol smile, teeth, tongue and all! If you want a dog that is going to make you laugh every single day, this is your guy! He likes to chew up toys so he would need some tough toys that make him work for it! Kane is a total ladies man, and really only warms up to ladies! He has a really hard time trusting men so it would be best for Kane to go to a home that has no men. Kane is a big boy, and he can break out of a crate if he wants to, so he needs a strong crate that he cant break out of!

Children over 10yrs old would be best due to his size. Teddy requires at least a 5 ft high fence.

He can be timid with strangers and is said to be protective of his home. Solomon is super smart and knows all kinds of tricks...'sit,' 'shake,' 'down,' and 'roll-over.' He is treat-motivated (he takes them gently) and treats are a great way to win his trust. He would probably do best in a quieter home where there isn't a lot of foot traffic. If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting Solomon, please fill out an application on-line at www.puppyhillfarm.com and we will get back with you to set up a meet and greet appointment.

animal.description:
Archer is a four year old male pit mix. He is a solid boy, weighing around 90 lbs. This guy is a total goof and, since coming into our care from a partner shelter where he tested positive for heartworm, his playful side has really started to show. Archer does need a firm owner that won’t let him get away with behaviors like occasional jumping and leash grabbing. With consistency, he has shown us he already knows some basic commands like sit. He is a gentle treat taker. Due to the jumping, Archer would probably do best in a home with older or no children. He also needs a home without other dogs, but what other dog could you need besides Archer? If you agree, apply to adopt online at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Marilyn is two years old and weighs approximately 40 pounds. She will need a special home and an extremely patient adopter. She is terrified of everything. Marilyn has been in a foster home for four months and is learning to trust people. She needs a securely fenced yard and a doggy door so she can come and go. She will not go through a doorway if a person is near it. She will not come when she is called, but she wants to be with the pack. Marilyn plays with her canine foster siblings and follows them and her foster mom everywhere they go. She will let you pet her but still backs away first as if she will be struck. She feels safe in two spots in her foster home and will only sit and lie down in those two spots. If you would like to provide the special home that Marilyn needs, please complete our adoption application. Her adoption fee is $175 and includes age appropriate vaccines, spay and a microchip

animal.description:
Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Carlos (aka Kane) is just the sweetest, big lover boy in the world. He's very handsome with a big melon head, and will be an excellent couch buddy. He's about 3 1/2 years old, about 45 lbs now, and has a glossy all black short coat. What a handsome goofy boy ! He loves people, but he's too active for very small children. He's good with non-aggressive dogs, and loves his doggy girlfriends. He had a rough start in life, but he's back on track now. He's filled out, gained his muscle tone and is very athletic. He'd be a great agility dog and/or running buddy. He's all vetted, healthy and ready for his new home. He'd love to go to obedience school and learn to walk properly on a leash, but he's very smart and will learn quickly. He needs a securely fenced yard for exercise and play. He loves life, enjoys his food, and he's very playful with toys, balls and beef bones. He will be an excellent companion for some lucky humans. Please contact Dee at K9RescueVa@gmail.com with any questions, and to schedule a meeting with this sweet boy.

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/muttloverescue
Follow us on Twitter: @Muttlove_Rescue

animal.description:
All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description: Tanner is a super sweet boy who smiles a lot!  He has dimples and a wrinkled nose when he smiles (not in pics because he is to wiggly when smiling to take a picture!).  He is about a year old and eager to please and will do almost anything for a treat.  He was attacked by another dog recently and is healing up well and will be ready for his forever very soon. He would probably be best as an only pet.  He loves people but can be a little jealous and does not like to share his people with others sometimes.  He was previously an outside dog but is adapting really well to being inside and LOVES being on the couch with you.  He hasn't has a single accident in his crate and understands to go outside to potty.  He likes to jump up and hug so would be best with older kids but we are working on this.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Buddy and his bonded, older companion Prissy were rescued from the New Orleans area when their owner went into nursing care. Sadly, Prissy had health issues and passed away earlier this year so now Buddy is looking for his forever family alone. Buddy is a senior and is the sweetest boy. He loves to cuddle and be close to his person. He is quiet and seldom barks. Buddy is house trained and will take himself out of the doggy door to do his business. He is crate trained but doesn't require crating when his foster parents are away from the home. He is not destructive and doesn't chew. Buddy loves plush toys with squeakers and enjoys treats of all kind. He gets along with the dogs in his foster home and enjoys spending time in the yard. It is not known how Buddy does with cats but he does enjoy attention from older, gentle children. One of the reasons that Buddy's former family did reach out to rescue for help is because Buddy has seizure disorder and they were worried about managing his condition. Buddy's seizures are currently very well controlled with CBD oil but have also been well managed with phenobarbital. Buddy is very healthy otherwise. Buddy is a loving boy and deserves to have a family of his own. Giving him daily medication for his condition is such a small thing to ask for all of the love that Buddy will give in return.
