animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Maddie was rescued from a very small Dallas area shelter after being found stray. She had a microchip and when the shelter reached out to her owner Maddie's family claimed to not know her even though a second contact on the file confirmed the owner's identity. It was very sad to think that she was unwanted. Maddie was skittish and hand shy when she arrived at her foster home. It was evident that she had not always been treated well but with time and patience she is learning to trust again. She now enjoys meeting new people and loves being petted. Maddie is house trained and uses a doggy door. She doesn't particularly like being crated. We suspect that she may have spent too much time being locked away in her previous home. She isn't destructive and hasn't required crating while being in foster care. She gets along well with the other dogs in her foster home. She enjoys attention from older, gentle children. We aren't sure how she does with cats.Even though Maddie is considered a senior she loves to run and would appreciate a yard with room to stretch her legs. She is very healthy and has the energy of a younger dog without being hyper. Maddie will find a dog bed when she is ready to sleep. She is not comfortable being on furniture or on the big bed so it is likely she was not allowed in her former home. Maddie is somewhat vocal and will answer when you talk to her so she may not be the best suited for a home with shared walls. Since Maddie wasn't cherished by her former family, we are hoping to find her a new family that can help her to forget any past mistreatment. Maddie may take a little time to warm up when arriving in a new home, but we know that the love she will give will make it all worthwhile.

animal.description: Oh, where shall I begin with Stormy's tale? This poor dog is from West Texas and endured a harrowing trauma to reach us here at BCRA. She had been found dragging a chain. Not an uncommon sight in those parts but this time, the chain had been roped through her neck. Yes, you read that right. Her neck was sliced open and a chain pushed through it to keep her in her yard. She escaped anyway and found angels that put her back together again. Stormy is dog aggressive and we assume cat aggressive as well. Despite all of this, she's AMAZING. LOVES people and kids, loves bones, toys, food, zero food aggression at all. She's tough on a leash but that's workable. She's 4 years old, smart as a whip and loves car rides. We believe leash and muzzle training will do her good. She was in a foster home with a docile large male dog in Texas and she loved him. But for now, we think being the only pet might be the best. To adopt, apply at www.brasscityrescue.org

animal.description:
Okay, long story short, my name is Kala and I am looking for the love of my life!  I am a 4 year old, 39lb., shepherd mix beauty.  I am an independent snuggle bug.  I enjoy snuggles and pets but I draw the line at smooches...yuck.  Do you know how many germs are in the human mouth?!  I'm offended just thinking about it.  I am house trained and crate trained.  I am also a great friend to other dogs and cats.  I need another dog friend in my new home. Children make me very nervous...way too many germs on those guys so none of those small germ factories in my home please!  I like on my own for a very long time before Rescue One saved me.  Because I was so independent for so long and didn't always have great interactions with humans, I need my forever person to be full of love, patience, and understanding.  I will need time to relax and adjust.  My best friend will need to be extra careful about my safety.  I am a skittish little girl who hates to be cornered.  I need a 6ft privacy fence in my forever home and to be aware I am a big flight risk.  I am okay on a short leash with a harness, but do not enjoy that leash contraption around my neck! No thank you!  I am a sweet little munchkin and I've been through a lot.  I cannot wait to find my soulmate and have every day be glorious because we are together and safe.


My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Peter!

I was brought into the shelter as a stray with an open wound under my left eye. It was pretty bad but the medical staff helped me start healing. I was transferred to the rescue so that I could continue to heal in a home-like environment.

We don't know how I was injured but it could have been because I'm a bit of a scrapper as I have some old injure scars on my back leg that look like they healed without medical attention. I may not be a spring chicken but I do like to assert 6lb myself and some dogs don't like that. Unfortunately, I don't take their corrections well and I will stand my ground. This could be because though I can see, my eyesight isn't the best so my judgment of their intent can be a little off.

Yes, I am older but I am also very alert and I love to walk about and explore. When we are walking, even though the house, I like to be all 4 on the floor rather than being carried. But once we are on the couch or the bed, I love to cuddle up and fall asleep on you. Careful though, I will try to jump off of the bed on my own and I will injure myself if I do.

As an older dog, I will need to have regular medical checkups. I do have a heart murmur that needs to be checked but it's not an issue for me. While in care I received my vaccines, a micripchip, I was neutered, and I had a dental. My teeth were beyond bad but I was able to still keep some of my teeth! I will need to eat dry kibble to keep them.

I'm looking for a person or a couple who wants to spend most of their time with me. I prefer to be an only dog and please, no kids. If you think we may be a good match, or you would like to get to know me better, please complete an application by going to my profile, clicking the button at the bottom of the page and you will be contacted soon. animal.description:
Sweet Heidi was found running loose near an employees home. She is very sweet and her previous home life left her unsure of others in the beginning. She is very gentle with the staff and very anxious to please us in all she does. She loves attention & makes us laugh at meal time. She is a huger and loves a good back scratching.

We have found Heidi does not do well with other dogs. She adores humans and just wants to snuggle & hug them!  We have also determined she needs a fenced in yard and it needs to be a large sturdy fence because she is a jumper. She walks pretty well on a leash for the most part but we have found while in a foster home she is easily distracted so she may not potty while on a walk. She will need much more leash training which is why a fenced yard is essential. She will always potty when let out in the yard. 

Heidi has so much love to give and just needs a chance with a family that will love her back and appreciate all she has to offer. She currently resides with us here at the clinic. If you are interested in adopting her please fill out an application. Once approved we will contact you for meet & greet.

animal.description:
Meet Keke... This sweet girl has found herself at a local shelter and they have reached out for help. KEKE, a 15 yr old — 22 lb Boston Terrier/French Bulldog mix, was selected for rescue transport to Maine through the shelter but sadly the shelter was notified by their rescue partners that all transports to the Northeast have been suspended indefinitely. They adore this resilient senior sweetie, and from our perspective, she deserves to spend her golden years in a comfy bed, being spoiled and cherished, by people who love her! ? A noisy shelter was NO place for a senior! Before her doting mom passed away, she wrote the following about her "baby" in hopes her new family would love Keke as much as she did:

"She is a very gentle, sweet, spoiled gal and deserving of so much love. ? She likes to "communicate" with people. Keke is hard of hearing, but please don't yell at her! She will pout in a corner if she thinks that you are mad at her. ? She likes French-cut green beans and chicken mixed in with her dog food. ? And, she loves "cookies" after her meals. ? Keke sleeps with a blanket, and will cover herself up in the blanket through the night. ? At her age, she still likes to go on leisurely walks. Her nickname is Best Good Dog!"?

Keke is still very active, and she is house trained, too. She is friendly with other mature, calm-natured dogs her own size or smaller, but her patience with playful "in your face" younger dogs sometimes wears thin. Can you blame her?! ? If you wish to open your home and heart to Keke, please come in and meet her. She'll surprise you with her zest for life! 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

https://form.jotform.us/70898112177159

animal.description: !!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! DOCTOR BUTTS - A#43651716Pictures:Doctor Butts snugglin' up in foster care - https://photos.app.goo.gl/4qUcv5LX2TNnPUUD6Dog meets:Doctor Butts, Monteza and Bruiser - https://youtu.be/Q_9jachvs38Doctor Butts and Alfy - https://youtu.be/KkvANWB0R6gIntake Type: (1/20) StrayWeight: 93 lbsMedical Observation:(2/10) Patient presented to clinic due to concerns of decline in the home- foster reports lethargy, decreased appetite, panting, regurgitation and coughing. On examination, patient is BAR and hydrated but has a frequent dry cough, followed by the occasional hack. Left hock and lymph node remain small and comfortable on palpation. Discussed with foster continued concern that patient has pneumonia and may be developing reflux from constant hacking, as well as likely GI upset due to multiple antibiotics. Performed 4DX- negative x 4. Gave 400 mL SQ fluids, cerenia and famotidine injection. Dispensed additional week of AmoxiClav, Baytril, and Fortiflora. Dispensed Omeprazole (40 mg) PO BID x 7 days and two boxes of Cerenia (24 mg). Gave bag of Fresh Pet. Recommend discontinuing doxycycline at this time- if hock begins swelling again, may need to restart.(2/7) Patient presented to clinic for recheck of swelling in left hind hock- swelling has nearly completely resolved and popliteal lymph node has returned to normal size. Foster reports patient has developed exercise intolerance and still has a cough and occasional elevated respiratory rate despite course of doxycycline. Otherwise, patient is doing well- eating, drinking, urinatingand defecating normally. Blood was drawn and urine collected for CBC/Chem/UA/TT4. Consulted with IDEXX veterinarian. Discussed concern for possible low grade pneumonia and tick borne illness responding to doxycycline. Recommend complete course of enrofloxacin, extending AmoxiClav and completing 30 day course of doxycycline. Then, repeat blood work to assess thyroid. Neuter once URI/pneumonia has resolved for suspected BPH with possible prostatitis.(1/21) Vet Check - Patient is a senior, over conditioned dog with a large swelling around the left hock with pressure sores and a swollen local lymph node- r/o soft tissue infection vs septic arthritis vs injury vs neoplasia. Recommend starting with senior blood work and radiographs. Stable but urgent. Requires promotion for rescue willing to provide needed diagnostics and care. Behavior Observation: (1/22) Lifesaving - Stationary lying in front of kennel, allows leashing easily, halts going back into kennel, cannot be lured with treats, whale eyeing. Had to be muzzled and carried/lifted back into kennel. Minimal pulling on leash. Slow walker, lots of sniffing. Tense/allows some handling. Flinches to touch. Takes treats gently. Sniffs assessors but does not solicit interaction. TTA. (1/21) Vet Staff - Quiet, friendly. (1/20) Finder - Nice, friendly, calm, takes treats gently.This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact adopt@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster.We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more!Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description: At this time, all dog adoptions are being conducted by appointment only. Please click the link on our Adopt page (by species) to make an adoption appointment.Have you ever wanted a dog that is silly, stubborn, awkward, hilarious, protective, and smart all rolled up into one giant package? Hi, I'm Lilly, and that's me! I am 7 and a half years old, and my shelter friends have no idea what breed I might be, but I sure am pretty. I'm a big girl at over 100 lbs. I need to lose some weight because the extra pounds are heck on my hips, but my love of peanut butter is not helping. In fact, it's the way straight to my heart. It also helps me do things that I am normally not a fan of doing. I can be a bit nervous in new situations and around new people, so we will need a proper introduction or two. I want to be up front though, I am not a fan of most men. I don't want to get into my past, but I do want to be clear about that. Once I trust you, we are friends for life and my silly side comes out. I think playing tug-of-war and chasing a ball are about the two most fun things a gal can do. Have I mentioned I know just about every command your heart could desire? Sit, down, paw, sit pretty, leave it, drop, and even speak! I also do an outstanding impersonation of a monkey when I want your attention.I love going for walks, taking car rides, and seeing the sights. I don't want to live with young children, and I will probably be too much for cats. A mellow canine brother that knows I am the queen bee might be okay. If I am your kind of fabulous (and why wouldn't I be?), fill out an inquiry about me today. I am currently being doted on in a foster home, but I'm ready to stretch out in a home of my own.

animal.description: Clayton is a 2 years old, 13 lb Rat Terrier mix. Clayton’s back is broken, and he is a paraplegic. Don’t feel sorry for him, that doesn’t slow him down one bit. Clayton is a happy little guy. He scoots around the house (and outside when he has a drag bag on) and, once we get the pee scalding healed on the inside of his legs and his neuter incision heals, he will be rockin and roll’n in his own set of wheels. Clayton is getting used to being held and having diapers being put on, etc. It seems the injury he sustained happened recently, so things like putting on a diaper is very new to him. We have no idea what happened to him. Clayton will make you happy with his joy of life and his overall puppy happiness. Clayton will take a bit more work than a puppy who has 4 legs that work, but he is so worth the time and little extra effort. Looking for a fantastic foster or a fabulous forever family.

animal.description:
Thunder has come such a long way and we could not be more proud of this beautiful boy - he truly is one of our favorites. He has learned how to fetch, which is huge, and it is his favorite part of the day. Everyone continues to fall in love with him when meeting him. He's improving his communication when seeing other furry friends and to say I'm proud is an understatement!

Thunder is such a gentle giant and a love bug. He loves meeting new people and receiving all of the belly rubs. He is working on his communication when seeing other dogs, because he gets so excited to see new furry friends. He knows sit, stay, come, look, shake & other paw, down, touch, and leave it. He does great on the leash and really enjoys the outdoors. He is potty and crate trained and doesn't bark (unless someone knocks on the door). He snores just like a human and is very chill!

animal.description:
St. Nick is a jolly boy! St.Nick is soooo sweet. He kisses everyone in the family and wants to cuddle nonstop! Since he tends to get overly excited on a leash he has been working on his manners as well as working on making new dog friends.

This poor boy had a hard life and it is only fair he is a bit apprehensive about the outside world. He is working with our trainer and making great strides in his confidence, walking with other dogs that show attention and attending events for a short while until he gets comfortable. He is a smart boy and wants to please so bad but had an unfair start at life. So we are working on redoing that and it takes some time. He loves all his humans. He's such a sweet natured pup. He loves playing with other dogs and is glued to his foster when home. He thinks he's a lap dog so we're working on those boundaries. 

He's house broken and not to mention incredibly photogenic. This sweet boy weighs 50 pounds and is almost 7 years old. Found surrendered to a shelter with his eye barely attached. How long had he been suffering? It appeared he had been hit by a car. As soon as we heard about this guy we scooped him up to get him checked out. The first thing was removal of the eye; there was no saving it but it adds to his charm. He is a happy, healthy boy now.

animal.description:
Josie is another sweet neglected pup found as a stray and brought to the shelter. As you can see, Josie is now healed and ready to rock any doggy beauty pageant. She loves people and cuddles and car rides with the windows down and the air in her jowls. 

I have never seen a dog that reminds me so much of a mountain lion. Josie is 2-3 years old and would like to describe herself to you:
I've been accused of being a "Stage 5 Clinger, but I prefer "Snuggle Buddy. I'm a true homebody, who prefers Netflix and cuddles on the couch over nights out on the town. I'm shy at first but once I get to know you I will shower you with all my love. I am equal parts blanket hog and hiking companion. Enjoy the outdoors? Well so do I! I absolutely love to stretch my legs by the lake, at the park, or just around the neighborhood; lucky for you I'm not picky! Once I warm up I'm a big goofy bundle of enthusiasm, so I need to join a family with adults or older children. I'm in the market for a forever best friend so if you pick me, it's a win win!

Josie would make a great walking partner as she loves walks and hikes. She's very FRIENDLY but takes a minute to warm up as new people and dogs can make her a little nervous at first. Josie is also a super smart girl who enjoys playing fetch and knows sit and in (when told to go in her crate). She is working on stay and down. 

Josie's perfect forever would include an active couple or family with a yard for her to play in. She would be fine with another fur sibling but would also be ok as a spoiled only child. Josie is more than ready to move on to her forever home.

animal.description:
Maple has been with our rescue for a year now. She was rescued along with 30 other dogs, including some of her babies from a hoarding situation in East Texas.

The East pups were initially terrified of humans and human touch and sounds or quick movements. After a year in a foster home, Maple is happy to be with her female person. She hangs out with the other dogs in the home, even tries to play on occasion. Maple initially hid in a corner of a bedroom until she got more comfortable being around the house . She is now free to roam the house and go out when she wants. She still has her safe spaces she retreats to if frightened.

She is getting used to other people coming into the home, but is getting better with the rest of her family. Maple is a sweet, lap dog that loves to cuddle and sleep under the covers. She absolutely loves her morning walks in the neighborhood. She would be best in a home with a female to bond with in the family. She needs a patient foster who is willing to continue to work on her socialization skills; she will be a faithful companion to a patient adopter.

animal.description:
My first foster is beautiful Benny. He is playful and his sweet personality comes out more each day. He LOVES being outside and playing with his toys, and even gets to snuggle on the sofa for pets and naps!

Benny is only 10-12 months old and been let down by people; he sadly doesn't have that joyful carefree happy personality you would see in a typical puppy. He is scared and unsure of what might happen. We are working with him to gain that trust - perhaps for the first time in his life?

He's sweet and he wants love but you can tell he's still scared and unsure. The times he seems the happiest is when he is playing with other dogs. He trusts dogs but people he is wary. He crawls to you to collect a few pets and treats, you can tell he wants the love and attention but is wary of people.

He would do best in a household with other confident/social dogs. Probably no small kiddos. Someone with the time and patience to build trust and an experienced handler to help train with Benny to build confidence and set him up for success.

animal.description:
My name is Lemon I weigh 54 pounds. At three months I was rescued from a neglectful owner, I was dying of parvo. I was sent directly to the emergency vet and spent several days hospitalized. I am now a year old but my early experiences have left me very cautious and suspicious of new people. I am working on my trust issues but I learn quickly especially when treats are involved. Once I KNOW you, I LOVE you-but I need time, patience and an experienced owner who can keep helping my development. Love Lemon. 

Lemon is such a sweet loving girl, but first she needs to trust you. So slow intros with this cutie are a must. We are working on building Lemons confidence, she recently went to Home Depot to practice some of her new commands. Helping her overcome some of her fears and having fun too. She just needs a little patience and time and she will be such an amazing companion. Lemon was found sick, emaciated, dehydrated and pitiful. Living in deplorable conditions with several other dogs. One of outreach volunteers was able to get her into our care. She was only 3 months old and had parvo; she spent a week in the ER getting fluids and medicine to help combat the effects of parvo. We are determined to help this girl get the life she deserves. 

Lemon is doing amazing now, she gets to be a healthy, happy puppy now. You would never know she was ever sick. Beautiful, playful and ready for her happily ever after.

animal.description:
Look how hunky and handsome I am! This boy is the absolute sweetest. He lives for face scratches...and food! 

When rescued he was extremely underweight but is now a healthy weight at 80 pounds. Just looking into his eyes and you could tell he was sad and longing for a good home. Judging from the calluses on his elbows he had probably spent most of his life outside. This sweet, sweet senior needed out of the shelter and on to a better life than he's obviously known thus far. We\I absolutely fell in love with this precious boy and know you will too. 

His skin and coat are gorgeous, and his low back/hips seem to be better because he is playing and can now get up on the couch. He just wants love and attention...and a comfortable place to rest his head. He has such an easy going temperment. Loves his daily walks and good meeting new people on his walks. Dog friendly (with medium to large dogs), people friendly, kid friendly, house trained, crate trained. He's a little too interested in cats and small dogs. Barber is a sweet eight-year-old Rottweiler mix.He is very calm and gentle and chooses to stay close to his human friend. He is very loving. He gives kisses. He sits for treats. He wants to please. Barber is waiting to go home with you.

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process. Thank you for your interest in adopting a Dallas DogRRR.

animal.description:
This handsome guy is DIP. He was found dodging traffic on D.I.P and picked up by one of our volunteers. Dip is a lab mix around 1 year old. He’s a super friendly boy. He doesn’t meet a stranger and loves other animals. He could benefit for some basic training. He’s active and playful. He would do awesome with a active family that has a large yard and kids to play with. Also, he would do great in a home with another dog his size to wrestle and play with. He doesn’t mind the crate or car. He’s utd, hw tested and neutered! 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

If interested in Flo please send us an inquiry through Petfinder

Available in the DFW area only

Thank you

animal.description:
Please email info@HWHANIMALRESCUE.COM for questions or to see our rules and to download the Required Application www.hwhanimalrescue.com

Only apply if you meet the following criteria:
No other Pets in the home.
No small Children.

Jasper needs to be the only pet  - He needs someone who understands small dog behavior and that they always think they are in Charge,

Jasper
10 lbs
Aprox 7 to 8 years young.  
This guy has smallness on his size as the smaller the dog the longer the life!

Silky Terrier
Neutered / Up to date on vaccine. Also had a dental cleaning and extractions. (He no longer has any teeth). But still eats well.

In typical little dog fashion he is feisty in new situations. 
Jasper is a jerk, he can be nice for a short time - but then decides he is in charge and that is that.

*** We want to be 100% Transparent. He wants everyone to know he is in charge. Someone has to be willing to work with this and help fix his behavior.   He has never had someone willing to work with him so he was always allowed to get away with this bad behavior.

He can get pushy and a mean when he doesn't get his way - he will charge at you as if he wants to bite, but as he has no teeth - it will not break skin.

He needs someone who will help him understand the pecking order in the home. He needs structure and guidance.

We unfortunately do not have the funds to hire a pet behaviorist to work with him. We are hoping that there is someone out there who is working to take the challenge and take on Jasper

animal.description: She was rescued as a stray down south and has come a long way!  When she first came into the rescue, her only leash skill was her ability to slip them off and she would go crazy when she saw another dog.  Thanks to her foster homes, she now walks very well on a leash and only gets a little excited when she sees other dogs but is easily redirected.  She likes all people but does have a tendency to jump when she first meets someone.  When she first came in, she was thought to be dog reactive or aggressive, but since settling in to life off the streets, she has been able to make some dog friends, both male and female.  She can be very vocal when she first meets another dog and while playing but doesn't show any real aggression.  She is very food motivated and does show a high pray drive towards squirrels.  She is a strong dog and does need a knowledgeable handler who can continue to help her adapt to life in a home.

Ginny is a 8 year old pittie who came to our rescue after a Good Samaritan found her on the street. She was emaciated, in pain and was severely neglected. animal.description: !!! AVAILABLE for Adoption from Foster Care !!! MOCHI FKA JAMIE A#44007402Foster Email: roilaurel08@gmail.comMochi's Instagram: @mochi.dapitPhotos:Jamie in foster care! - https://photos.app.goo.gl/U17XR7Gkid45saX16Dog Meets:Jamie and Deku: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qpfFVy05HTgMochi is an amazing furball! Expect your day to be filled with her special hugs and kisses! She loves pretending to be a lap dog whenever you give her the chance, but she is more than happy chilling out on the rug next to you. She will do whatever it takes to be near her loved ones and loves her walks and saying hi to strangers. She does well on the leash if there aren't any distractions, is totally fine around people, but pulls a bit around other dogs. She knows "sit" and is learning how to do "paw"! Intake Type: (3/12) StrayWeight: 50.40 lbsMedical Observation:(4/26) Vet Check -- From memos under original A#44007402 sounds like Mochi was not doing well behaviorally in adoptive home, showed some aggression towards male owner when on the couch and also towards female owner when resting on her dog bed - possible resource reactivity. Recovering well from pyometra spay, very BAR with loose body language both in kennel and when in exam room here. Very mildly elevated temperature.Behavior Observation:(4/26) Per Vet Staff -- friendly, comes right up in kennel, no concerning behaviors.(4/25) Per Previous Owner -- We noticed she's had the following symptoms that have particularly escalated today: sleeping a lot, panting heavily while in a relaxed state, licking her lips/the air frequently, and diarrhea. We believe these be could be a side affects of the Clavacillin.- Additionally, earlier today, around 3 p.m. Mochi and I were sitting on the couch and she was in and out of sleep. Buddy came home, sat next to her and gave her a new toy. After sitting with her for a few minutes, he attempted pet her and she snarled and snapped at him. He moved away and tried to identify if it was the toy. We took the toy the away and took her on a walk and it seemed to help dissipate the situation and she was able to relax with us on the bed for a while. Later in the evening, all three of us were on the couch again and she began to lock eyes with Buddy and again, starting growling. We tried to coax her off the couch with treats and redirect her to her dog bed, but she either refused to move or would growl at Buddy anytime he got close. We let her be and separated ourselves from her, but later on she was panting very heavily and I went to check on her, she let me pet her head but then snarled and attempted to bite me.This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact adopt@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster.We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more!Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description:
Hi my name is Puck, and I am a 1.5 yr old  Shepherd Mix. I am a Tuba City Humane Society rescue pup who has been in training with Paw Creek Training. I am learning how to be a big boy. You see I was afraid of a lot of things and needed a leader to show me how to cope with new situations.  I am still a bit shy but with consistent love I promise to be your best boy ! 

Paw Creek Training has taught me how to walk properly on a leash, how to follow basic commands, but most of all how to be a confident trusting pup! In order to adopt me you have to be a strong confident leader that wants to take some classes with me.  Can you come to Cave Creek and take a few classes with me?  I sure hope so ! 

Paw Creek Training will teach you everything I have learned and how to grow our relationship. Because I am a cautious boy a quieter home would be best. No little humans under 12.  

Puck is a happy guy, that is playful and fun. He loves to play, he is doing well with the dog pack at Paw Creek Training. Because he has shown signs of food and toy aggression towards dogs in the past, he needs a strong leader. He is dog friendly. He has a lot of energy but it's not over the top. 

Puck is up to date on vaccinations and has been neutered and microchipped. Puck is at Paw Creek Training in north Phoenix. His adoption fee is $150.

We are a small rescue/foster group without an animal shelter. If you are interested in meeting Puck, please fill out an online adoption application, located here: http://tubacityhumanesociety.org/tuba-city-humane-society-dogcat-online-adoption-application/ with more information about our adoption process here:
http://tubacityhumanesociety.org/adoptions/

Once we receive your application, which answers basic questions for us, we will have a conversation with you, before setting up a meeting. For more information, please contact Deb at dfranklin@tubacityhumanesociety.org or by phone at (928) 853-1046 (No calls after 6 p.m. please.)

animal.description:
Requirements: A 6' or taller privacy fence, puppy mill experience, no children, someone w/o close neighbors/outside of city limits due to excessive barking

Josie
is a playful girl who had a rough start in life. She came into rescue as a one-year-old with almost no human interaction, so she will need a home that understands that she may never become a "normal" family dog. Since coming into rescue,
Josie
has made very few social gains. She is currently on a medication to help calm her nerves but it has only helped so much. She has learned to go potty outside or on a potty pad, but she is not 100% yet. She loves other dogs and is constantly play bowing at her foster siblings in attempts to get them to play with her. She also loves toys and tries to take as many toys as she can outside to play with in the yard when the weather is nice.
Josie
will take treats out of human hands but she does not let you pet her or hold her willingly. Her foster mom makes sure to provide her with treats and praise when she does pet or hold her, but
Josie
shakes and is very uncomfortable while interacting physically with humans.
Josie
is not a dog who you will take on walks, car rides, or to the dog park. As of now, she is a major flight risk, meaning if she sees a way to escape, she will, and you will not catch her.
Josie
is also a frequent fear-barker, especially when she is outside, so her ideal home would be someone without close neighbors or someone who lives outside of city limits. She has been in two different foster homes for quite some time and has plateaued on progress so that is why we are reaching out to our potential adopters with puppy mill experience.
Josie
's foster homes have tried every piece of advice given from professional trainers with very little gains. We are hopeful that more progress can be made since she is still young, but realistically, she will never be a social, cuddly pup.

2/1/21 1:06 AM

animal.description:
Morrison is an approximately 2 year old male pitbull terrier mix. He’s a big ole baby at around 65 lbs. He is neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, and micro-chipped. Morrison was rescued from a dog fighting operation back in January and is finally ready to start thinking about finding his forever family. He is not quite ready to make it official, but he would love to meet them and know who is waiting to spend his forever with him after he graduates training class! 

***This dog, along with the over 20 other dogs rescued from a fighting ring, has been assessed for behavior and temperament and approved for adoption. However, since we had training sessions donated to us, we are erring on the side of caution and slowly sending them all through behavioral training that will teach them basic manners and give them a good structure to build on with their forever family. Please inquire as to the status of this dog's training if you're interested in meeting and possibly adopting! The most important thing to us is to ensure that these dogs' horrendous past does not affect the future they deserve to have! ***

We do not have much information about where he is at with training (house training, leash training, etc.) The beginning of his new life has been focused on relaxing and healing, so this will come with more time. 

He loves to play with other dogs his size and gives good corrections if they push him too far. We think he would do best in a home with no young children or cats, and no alpha dog personalities.

We suspect he was born into the operation and has never known life as a house pet. :( Despite his rough start, he is a very sweet, happy boy. He just needs a patient, kind human being to show him what it is like to be part of a loving family. He is a very anxious car rider but is otherwise doing really great learning the ropes of “pet life." He is pending going to a training program that will teach him basic manners and give him a good structure to build on with his new family, but he will need continued training and patience likely for quite some time once in his new home. Morrison needs a resilient human that will fight FOR him. 

If you think you could be the right person for him and would like to meet him, please apply here: http://muttmisfits.com/adoption-application/

animal.description:
People say good girls go to heaven...but bad girls go everywhere.  I'm ready to go. Take me with you. I like to think of myself as delightfully difficult. and it may just be easier on you if you agreed. I'm the kind of girl that when my feet hit the floor each morning the devil says, "Oh crap, she's up!   Hey, I'm not perfect, buy I'm trying my best.  So, give me a break!  I’m a simple girl, I like pretty women, handsome bearded brunette men and breakfast food.

I know I'm just a dog but, if you feel sad, I'll be your smile, if you cry, I'll be your comfort.  And,if someone breaks your heart, we can use mine to live.  I'll always be by your side.

Note:  Great Pyrenees are considered a Giant Breed.  The average weight can be 100lbs. or more.  They bark, shed, and have a wanderlust, so secure fences are a must-have.  They are NOT off-leash dogs and a Pyr off-leash is called a "dis'a'Pyr".  Some Pyrs do well with other dogs and some don't because by the virtue of the breed traits they were bred to keep out intruders and can consider some dogs as intruders. While they make wonderful pets and family dogs, they aren't for everyone so be sure to understand and learn about the breed traits of this breed or any breed you might be considering.

animal.description:
Meet Chappy ;) 
This little guy came to us very very afraid & would bite when he felt threatened. He attached to women very quickly but was especially afraid of men. Sadly we are confident this little guy had been abused & it caused him to be very insecure. We knew we would have to do something for him to become adoptable. 

Chappy has come such a long way & even received professional training! He knows all of his commands including place, heeling, waiting for his food etc. He's a sensitive guy but has figured out this "pet dog" thing ;) 

He bonds easily to people but is scared of strangers. He needs someone that will put him up when there is company over at the house & advocate for him in public-- for example, don't let random people touch him unnecessarily. 

He coexists with my 6 other dogs but wouldn't be a good doggy playmate. He's more of a companion for a person. 

He would love a furever home that will understand they need to keep up with the structure & obedience once he's home.

Let us know if you're interested in this handsome guy longing for a place that understands his needs & where he can feel safe & secure forever! <3 

His adoption fee is waived to the perfect home!

animal.description:
*Sponsor Mia!- she needs ongoing vet care which you can sponsor on our secure site with a monthly contribution of as little as $10 - or help support her care with CBD from Zoorenity! This has been an extremely effective way to help her with her skin discomfort and generalized anxiety, keeping her relaxed and peaceful as she awaits her new home!

NAME: MIA FARROW

AGE/GENDER: 6 year old FEMALE

BREED: HOUND/ PIT BULL MIX

TEMPERAMENT: Friendly, Outgoing, Social

WEIGHT: 71 lbs.

HOUSE TRAINING: Good!

CRATE TRAINING: Good!

OTHER DOGS: Mia would do best as an only dog.

CATS: Good!

CHILDREN: Dog-respectful children, 8 and older

ADOPTION DONATION: $425

HEALTH: MIA is spayed, microchipped, flea treated, dewormed, and is current on vaccines. Mia has separation anxiety and is on prozac daily. Mia has a heart murmur, which may be due to taurine deficiency. This has been evaluated by a cardiologist who recommends another echocardiogram in a year's time to reevaluate.

Your adoption donation goes toward offsetting the cost of this vet care as well as other incidental costs of care.

HISTORY: MIA was surrendered to a shelter under no fault of her own and Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find MIA a great forever family!

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME:

MIA was surrendered with a case of mange and a skin infection with possible underlying allergies. MIA has undergone treatment and is doing great! Her skin has recovered remarkably, though she will require continued medication to help keep her skin issues at bay. MIA is currently living her best life with her foster family. She loves to relax by the fireplace, hang out in the yard and just be her sweet, chill self.

Mia is great with cats, small children, and small dogs. She gets agitated with larger dogs, although her tail keeps wagging even as she barks. She also uses her kennel like a dream. She's ready for her forever home with YOU!

Foster Update: Mia is a sweet and affectionate lady who just wants to love and be loved ALL the time! Her favorite thing would be to snuggle on the sofa with her people while maybe watching a movie, but her foster family doesn't want her to have bad habits, so they substitute lots of pets and belly rubs instead. She's SOOOO smart! Somewhere in her history, someone taught her a ton of commands, and her vocabulary is even bigger. Yesterday, you could see her trying to figure out out how to follow the command to "put on your coat". She kept looking at her coat but knew she couldn't put it on by herself. She came to Motley Zoo from the shelter, and before that was apparently on the streets in Tacoma.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and Martingale collar (or a harness, if necessary), depending on each dog's particular needs. Each dog also receives a "Tour Gear Bag" full of brochures, coupons, and supplies for your new pup!

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO:

Welcome to Motley Zoo Animal Rescue! We are a rock and roll themed, volunteer-run, foster based, 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization based in Redmond, WA.

Motley Zoo is a FOSTER BASED organization, which means our rescue animals are cared for in private foster homes (or partnering pet stores) where the animals receive one-on-one care and attention in a home environment until permanent placement is found. We do not have animals available for casual viewing and same day adoption. Due to the volunteer run structure and decentralized/ virtual nature of a foster based group, an approved application is required to make an adoption appointment for any of our animals.

If you are interested in one of our Adoptable Roadies, please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application (the auto-responder also has a link to our application). We will work toward getting you approved as an adopter so that we can set a time for you to meet your new best friend!

Motley Zoo also runs "Rock Star Treatment Dog Daycare" in Redmond, WA where proceeds from this service, help support our rescue's vet budget- however, this is NOT a shelter. For more information about daycare or training, check out www.rockstartreatment.org.

Please visit our website www.motleyzoo.org for more information!

Thanks for considering adoption- we look forward to helping you find your best match in a furry friend.

Rock on-

The Motley Zoo Crew

animal.description:
Hi Everyone! My name is Kieran – first, I should make it clear that I’m sassy and I don’t have the greatest attention span – so forgive me if I get side tracked. Speaking of tracks, have you ever followed an animals tracks and chased them? Tots funz. I like to chase things. I currently spend a lot of time at a tattoo shop which is pretty interesting! Lots of people coming and going. I like people. One time this really big fellow came in and we played with my toy for a while. He threw and I fetched it and then he threw it again and I caught it again and then he threw it again and I caught it again. I like to cuddle, so if you are sitting down, there is an approximately 129.66% chance I will try to lay on you. I really do love getting pets and love my walks. If you like to snuggle sometimes and walk sometimes, we’d probably be a cool match. I need to be the only animal in the house but that just means I get all the attention from my humans! 

Please fill out an adoption application here: https://www.meritpitbullfoundation.com/adoption-form

Our adoption fee is $250.

*All dogs receive the following prior to adoption: Distemper/Parvo Vaccine, Rabies Vaccination, Heartworm Test & Treatment (if needed) Spay/Neuter (no dog will ever be adopted out without being altered), and Microchip. *Puppies too young for rabies or final boosters will need to be vaccinated post-adoption at the expense of the adopter.
*All adopters must be at least 21 years of age.
*We will only place dogs with indoor ONLY homes.
*A home visit and application are required prior to adoption.
*We do check home owners insurance or with your landlord to ensure pit bull type dogs are accepted in your home or apartment.

IMPORTANT: Many homeowner's insurance companies have breed blacklists or "dangerous dogs" lists which include, but are not limited to, pit bulls, American Pit Bull Terriers, American Staffordshire Terriers, Staffordshire Bull Terriers, Rottweilers, Dobermans, Akitas, American Bulldogs, Chows and wolf-hybrids and WILL NOT insure you if they reside in your home or may cancel your insurance if you add a dog of these breeds to your home. If you rent, landlords may also have these same breed restrictions due to their insurance policies. Please check your homeowner's insurance policy or ask your landlord regarding breed discrimination before submitting this application to adopt a pit bull type dog.

animal.description:
Tucker is a beautiful boy with and even more beautiful heart. He was adopted as a puppy and returned as an adult at no fault of his own. When he was returned, our staff noticed a bit of a hitch in hit get-a-long and discovered it to be because of a torn cruciate in his hind leg. Tucker has since had surgery on his knee and runs and plays just like any other dog! He's impressively fast and LOVES fetch. He's a bit shy and needs more socializing with other dogs, but with the right match we think he will adjust just fine. No cats, please! He thinks they make a better treat than a playmate! Tucker's adoption fee is $195, which includes his neuter, microchip and up-to-date vaccines.

If you are interested in adopting please go to www.partnersforpetsil.org and fill out an online application. We hold adoptions at the O'Fallon IL Petsmart every Saturday and the Glen Carbon Petsmart every Sunday. Both days from 11:00 - 3:30. We are also at the Petco in Edwardsville Crossing every Sunday from 11:30-3:30.

animal.description:
Mason has a story to tell and he would love to share it with his new family. He was a stray for months and finally an awesome lady was able to get him in her backyard. He was skinny beyond belief, scared and covered in fleas. It took days to get this little guy to trust us enough to get him in a crate to go to the vet. Now that he knows his days of running and trying to survive on his own are over, he's starting to relax but he still needs to be introduced to new people slowly. He likes other dogs but needs slow introduction and does better with females. He would do best in a calm, quiet home. He knows sit and is good on a leash. Mason loves his walks and outside play time but can cuddle with the best of them. If you are looking for the perfect southern gentleman Mason is your man! 

** All of our Wigglers are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, hw tested/treated, and on preventatives. Most of our adoptable dogs need fenced in yards or an exercise regimen. Please read their description above closely. Our adoption fee is $350. For an application please send us your number and email address in a message. **

animal.description:
Name: Montana
Breed: German Shepherd Doberman Mix
Age: 5
Size: Large (90-105 lbs)
Cats: Yes
Dogs: No - Montana prefers to be the only dog
Kids: No 
Crate Trained/Housebroken: Yes 
****Breed Experience Required/will consider prior experience with similar protective dog breeds****
About Montana: 
Montana is a very loyal girl, extremely loving, affectionate, and protective of her people. Montana would be best suited for someone with an active lifestyle that can give Montana the physical and mental stimulation she requires, and has strong handling experience due to her strength and size. 
Montana's ideal person would be someone with a pack leader mentality that she can form a bond with, as Montana looks to her handler for consistency in her daily routine and direction when encountering new people or situations. 
We are looking for someone with breed experience/similar protective breed experience who has minimal foot traffic in the home, as Montana would thrive in a home with someone who understands the needs and the temperament of her breed. Montana requires slow introductions to new situations and people as she's extremely protective.
Montana loves to go for walks, run around chasing tennis balls, and has a soft spot for any game that involves water. 
Montana has successfully completed level 1 training with Our Companions and is excited to begin Level 2 with her handlers soon.
 Montana is spayed, vaccinated up to date, and microchipped. 
If Montana sounds like your girl, please fill out an application today

animal.description:
Tripod (aka Clooney) is 1-2 years old and weighs around 12 pounds. He is spunky and sweet. He's a goofy guy and makes our volunteers smile. He has a medium energy level and not hyper at all. He is loving and affectionate with his humans. He can be a bit shy at first, but warms up quickly. He is a very well-mannered dog. He was fostered in a home with children (between ages 7-15) and did well with them. He would make a wonderful family pet! He is good with other small/medium-sized dogs. Tripod is crate-trained and working on leash-training. He knows how to use a doggy door. He was brought to us as a stray by a good samaritan who told us he was found with a broken leg. Taken to our vet and given an x-ray, we noticed this was not the case! Tripod has a genetic defect in his back right leg. There is no cartilage between the bones there and causes his leg to stick out. Our vet told us he has been this way since birth and is not in any pain and that there is no reason to remove the leg other than aesthetic reasons (such as cropping ears or docking a tail). His front legs are also genetically deformed. He gets along perfectly fine as a house pet. Tripod gets around perfectly fine (see his video). The genetic defect in his legs does not greatly hinder his mobility; however, we are looking for a home for him that does not have stairs. He would do best in a home that is not looking for a walking companion, or a playmate for a current dog that plays rough, as this would put additional stress on his disability. He has had multiple x-rays and there is nothing that can help the genetic defects in his legs. Tripod is just a special little guy that is looking for a special family to call his own! He is sociable and sweet. He will make a great companion! His adoption fee is $325 which covers the cost of his x-ray, neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application, available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab and please read the paragraphs below for more details on our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
Peaches Goodman was born about November 18, 2010 and weighs about 32 lbs. She is a pretty girl with rough coated fur in the white/grey/black range. She is back with us after being gone for a few years - sadly, her human dad has passed away and her human mom is very ill. Peaches has some reluctance to us reaching for her quickly and when you have company she is distrustful of humans coming into her home and will need to be crated or put in a separate room. She is wonderful with the humans that she knows and trusts. Peaches has a nice energy for her age and is pretty good on leash and enjoys the activity. She is wonderfully house trained. Overall, sadly she is an anxious girl and needs a human(s) that will satisfy her energy needs and someone that lives in a rather calm lifestyle without a lot of other humans coming and going. She shivers and can get barky when she is stressed and when going in the car a Benedryl has been beneficial. Peaches does well with the other dogs here. In April 2019 she was diagnosed with mammary carcinoma with a life expectancy of 1-2 years, but if that special human doesn't come along she will be loved and cared for here for whatever time she has left.

Update: After Peaches failed two foster homes we are considering her a JR sanctuary pet. Did you know that there are very special dogs and cats who call Joyful Rescues home?

Peaches is what some may call "un-adoptable ."

Joyful Rescues remains committed to our Sanctuary Dogs and Cats. They will stay with us for their natural lives and we will care for and love them. We will be their forever family.

We wish we could do it alone but we need your help. We are looking for people who can help us with Peaches care. Please click the link below and donate. Peaches thanks you.

https://www.paypal.com/donate

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

Online Application

Love, Nala

animal.description:
Prince is a sweet, frosty-faced gentleman that is so deserving of a great home. He was surrendered in June, 2019 after spending his life in a home when the landlord said he had to go. Prince is around 8 years old now and this lab/pit mix just wants to go home. He is used to home-life, and loves his blankets and curling up with people on a comfy bed. He has little interest in toys, preferring to get lots of attention from whoever will give it to him. Prince has learned lots throughout his life, and will sit, offer a pawshake, lay down, and ever roll over when asked. He is strong, but he walks well on a leash. Prince has a permanent head-tilt, but it doesn't seem to affect his mobility at all. He doesn't have much interest in other dogs but doesn't dislike them so if you're interested in Prince, bring in your dog and we'll see how it goes. He will need a cat-free home. You'll love this sweet, older guy if you give him a chance. File#29515 6/28/19 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Prince.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description: Billy is a super sweet senior boy. This pit mix is small in stature, weighing in at 35-40 pounds, but he is big in love. Billy is 10 years old and was thrown away by his family, so he is looking for a loving family with whom he can spend his retirement years. Billy is selective with other dogs. He does not like cats. He is up to date on vaccinations, heartworm and Lyme negative, microchipped, crate trained, and almost completely house trained. He has been neutered and had the tumor on his lower lip removed. He would need a family that is mostly at home. Billy may have a few quirks, but after being thrown away, wouldnt you? animal.description: My name is Dante. I'm a 6 year old Cane Corso. I was set to be euthanized in another shelter but the rescue saved me. I was emaciated and very sick. I am doing much better now though. I'm up to date on vaccinations, flea treated, wormed, heartworm/lymes negative, and microchipped. I'm housebroken and working on obedience. I don't care much to be crated. I love toys and I'm always ready to play. The thing I love the most though is being with my person. We know Dante is an extremely handsome dog with a fun personality. He absolutely is not a dog for everyone though. He does have some guarding issues most likely due to the abuse he endured before he came to us. He has multiple requirements for adoption. Dante will only be considered for individuals with cane corso or similar breed experience. The home must have a secure, fully fenced in yard with no other dogs, no children and humans who will not be gone for more than 7-8 hours of the day. If you do not meet these requirements, your application will not be screened or considered for Dante. If you meet all requirements and are interested in adopting Dante, please complete an application.

animal.description: Myra just said good-bye to her last litter of puppies. She won't have to worry about having puppies any more. Now she can enjoy just being a dog. Her ears are listening for signs that someone is interested in her. Myra is a 6 year old German Shepherd Dog who is up to date on vaccinations, heartworm negative, lymes positive (this will need to be monitored for flare ups), flea treated, wormed, spayed, and microchipped. Myra is getting a little older and has some aches and pains, so we have her on several supplements that she would need to remain on after adoption. She is also on medication twice a day for pain/anxiety. She tends to be a bit nervous when around strange people or in a new situation. Once she's comfortable though, she's very friendly. She generally prefers to keep to herself or be with her person. She tolerates calm dogs but would ideally do best as an only dog or with one that is indifferent to other dogs. She does not appear to like cats. NO children because of her nervousness and activity level. Myra loves toys and loves to play alone or with her person. animal.description: The Save-A-Pet licensed humane investigators rescued me from being left outside in a small pen with little attention. The parents didn’t want a dog so the son kept me outside with very little interactions. As a result, I didn’t acquire some skills that puppies with caring families would learn, like sharing toys with people or protecting items that I think are mine. I was then quickly adopted and my family worked really hard in helping me catch up on everything that I had missed during the earlier months of my life. I learned a lot of things but still have more to learn and I’m quite willing. I’ve lived with a little dog and with a large dog. I really enjoy doggie play groups and I can play forever. So while I may no longer be a puppy, I need some adults willing to continue teaching me a few things. It may not be easy for most and it may take me a while to understand that but I am ready, are you?

animal.description:
Mona is a 3yo (1-17) and 8lb Long-hair Chihuahua that was surrendered. Crate-trained and progressing well with house-training when kept to a schedule. Mona is moderately timid and will require a dedicated owner to gain her trust and build her confidence. She would do well in a home with or without other dogs. Full-time small children would likely not be her forte, but visiting kids with strict supervision should be an option. Adoption Fee - $200 

Adoption not an option for you at this time? Consider a sponsorship! We spend appx $20/mth to feed and properly medicate a small dog, and some dogs may spend several months in foster care before their forever home is found. Sponsorships allow us to save more lives! PayPal.me/LaurensZoo or Venmo @LaurensZoo 

E-mail LaurensZoo@yahoo.com for more info! ***Please check your Spam Folder for our reply. We send out a lot of e-mails and have recently been getting complaints about not promptly responding to inquiries. Several servers filter our responses as Spam*** 

~~~AVAILABILITY INQUIRIES: If the dog is still posted then he/she is available. We may have already accepted applications but have not chosen one yet. Please send yours if you'd like to be considered. A "pending" status means that the pet is spoken for, but the adoption has yet to be finalized. This pet may become available again if the adoption is not completed within a reasonable amount of time. 
~~~LOCATION: We do not have a physical location where all of our dogs are housed nor do we have "business hours". We are made up of a network of private foster homes and sometimes use boarding. Once we have received your application, we can provide you with details and arrange a "meet and greet" when possible. We require an application before any meetings will be arranged. 
~~~CATS/KIDS & DOGS: If we don't specifically mention cats/kids in the bio then we don't know exactly how a particular dog will react to them. If we suspect there will be aggression then we will say no to cats/kids. However, every dog needs to be introduced correctly to a house with cats or kids in it. Each dog and each cat/kid will have different chemistry together so there is no way to tell how they will act until the dog is in the home. Puppies less than one year of age can always go to a home with cats or kids, but they too need to learn. With a little effort, dogs and cats/kids can live together...but don't forget that dogs will be dogs so sometimes you will need to step in. 
~~~OUT-OF-STATE ADOPTIONS: We will consider adopting to all states, but transport options are limited to some areas. Adopters are responsible for all additional fees associated with transporting a pet out-of-state.

animal.description:
ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

Meet Rocky!

Rocky is a super adorable, super active, super athletic, super playful little man. The vet thinks he is about 1.5 years old. Rocky loves, loves, loves playing and racing around with another active dog so we are requiring Rocky to go to a home with a securely fenced yard and a similar activity level of dog companion, not a senior dog, who will not appreciate, or be able to keep up with him! He loves to pal around with Tala, another of our dogs (posted).

Rocky is very unhappy and vocal when left alone, but a doggie playmate will reduce his separation issues. He is not a good choice for apartment living and he doesn’t like children. Rocky also has some resource guarding issues so he needs a human (or humans) who have experience with training and leadership. He needs to learn boundaries, and sharing. 

Such a cutie!

Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf
If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

Momentarily distracted with treats but then returns to jumping on handler again. After two to three minutes, finally disengages and explores yard before returning to handler with less energy. animal.description:
REMY: 3yo, Kelpie Mix, Spayed Female, NEEDS HOME OUTSIDE OF THE CITY 

Little by little, she's discovered herself. Remy has been with us through thick and thin aka for most of 2020, and what a journey it's been to watch her blossom. She was completely shut down when we took her in early this year, and though she's still a special case, she's found happiness and is ready to find her soulmate. She doesn't warm up immediately, especially with men, and she can't handle city stress, but if you have plenty of patience she is well worth the investment. This very shy 3-year-old Kelpie mix came from a rough past, so she'll need an understanding forever family with a resident dog that lives out of the city. Also plenty of mental and physical stimulation brains make up at least half of her 28 lbs. Her foster mom says: I cant even explain how special Remy is. She may be a bit nervous in new scenarios, and it will take someone with patience to earn her trust and guide her, but it is a small price to pay once she lets you in. Shes still not fully confident, and it makes me sad to think about what could have brought her to that level of unease, but shes made huge strides. Every little win is a victory and makes it that much sweeter. Loud noises make her want to run inside, but shes getting better. Shes letting go of the fear and more interested in smelling or interacting. Shes very smart potty trained, learning an obstacle course we built in the yard, and watches TV! She loves to lay and cuddle with me and smiles so much when she gets to wiggle on her back on a pile of soft grass or my bed. Its so funny, when she doesnt respond to 'come here,' I say, 'Bye, Remy,' and she bolts towards me. Such a smarty pants. We all love, love this awesome girl! Her loyalty is truly unparalleled. Thank you SO MUCH for rescuing Remy and pulling her into a new world where she will always be loved and treated with kindness." Interested in adopting? Submit an application at socialteesnyc.org or email your point person if youve already been approved!

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

animal.description:
Zane has been in his foster home healing from the trauma of being a young pup in a shelter.    He has adjusted very well thanks to his four-legged foster siblings in the home.  His older sister keeps him in check and is showing him good manners while the younger ones teach him how to play.   Of course, his foster mom has taught him that humans are safe and can be trusted.
Zane is a sweetheart with a bit of a strong-willed streak, so he will need continued training and leadership to make sure he grows into a well-balanced adult.  He is great with other dogs and his home really needs another, we think an adult female would be best, but a male who is a good mentor may be okay also.  He is also learning that mouthing and jumping, while a normal puppy behavior, are not acceptable.   He’s still working on that.
What Zane did learn very early on in his foster home was when he should be fed.  He was very very thin when he came in, so he got extra meals throughout the day.  When Zane’s foster mom found him sitting by the door leading to the food, she knew he was a smart boy.  It was, indeed, mealtime.  Then, just to reinforce how intelligent he was, when his foster was just a little bit late with another meal, Zane went to the kitchen, retrieved his bowl, and brought it to her.  Yep, he’s a smart, growing boy.
Puppies are a life-long commitment. They need time, training, vet care and healthy feeding to become good canine citizens. Don't even think of adopting a puppy unless you intend to invest the time and money and commitment required, and you can expect to lose a few good shoes along the way!

If you are interested in me, please contact us at puppies@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application.

The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100% tax deductible.

Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

We show our dogs at adoption events every weekend! Please click on events at Events to see where we'll be next! Coastal German Shepherd Rescue of Southern California is a non-profit 501(c%293 public charity dedicated to finding loving homes for abandoned German Shepherds. Your tax deductible donations go to support these very deserving animals. Coastal was formed to serve communities in the counties of San Diego, Orange, Los Angeles and the Inland Empire. We are committed to finding loving permanent homes for the orphaned dogs in our care. Coastal is an all volunteer, no-kill, 501 (c%29 3 non profit organization.

animal.description: Daisy was originally found as a stray in Crosbyton. No one came forward so she was placed for adoption. Her original owner then came forward and claimed her. Daisy spent approximately a year with her owner but then he became unable to care for her. She was brought back to our rescue and has been here since November 2019. Daisy is a great girl. She is very high energy but once she gets that out she will relax. She needs lots of exercise. She would make a good companion for an active individual or couple. She would be great with older kids but is too rowdy for smaller kids. She gets along with other dogs but needs to be introduced properly.
