animal.description: !!! Located at ACCT Philly, 111 W Hunting Park Avenue, Philadelphia PA !!!Mellow A43990918Intake Type: (3/10) Stray -- Public Drop Off Mellow is my name and I'm ready to find my forever family.When I first got to the shelter I was very scared and nervous. But the more time I spent with my volunteer friends, the more I've opened up. I enjoy playing with tennis balls and I like to play with other dog friends!I really don't like being in my kennel though. I give my volunteer friends a really hard time when they are putting me back. Sometime it takes two of them.I know I'm a great dog and once you meet me you'll see that.Please consider bring me home, I promise I'll be your best friend for life!Dog Meets:Mellow and Artica: https://youtu.be/upJJZ2qezY4Mellow and Artica 2: https://youtu.be/ZNWQqeEJEsoMellow and Artica 3: https://youtu.be/3qKEcPQgfE8Mellow and Spike: https://photos.app.goo.gl/zqLqmdWFqaBNxHLr9Mellow and Rowan: https://youtu.be/0koPsiAK3GsMellow, Koala, Candy Cane and Lexx: https://youtu.be/qPUDVRfa0TIMellow and Lexx: https://youtu.be/7suUdIYsgUMKoala, Millennium Falcon and Mellow: https://youtu.be/mmbo0AC6waYMellow and Millennium Falcon: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YW8bP38dVsUPhotos: https://www.flickr.com/photos/185100251@N08/shares/T62Hddhttps://flic.kr/s/aHsmMdKKFkhttps://www.flickr.com/photos/185100251@N08/shares/6c6RWjVideos:Mellow Outside -- https://photos.app.goo.gl/Qq4gEKimVqT2GhMk7Mellow loves his Best Volunteer Friend! -- https://youtu.be/vXaO0C9EM5oMellow laying -- https://youtu.be/dGC4Yzi_oFQEnjoying the Grass -- https://youtu.be/9-tliHtGUzMMedical Observation:(3/16) This dog has been observed to have shelter acquired upper respiratory infection (URI), or a "doggy cold". They have been moved into isolation area and are started on medication, and will be monitored for resolution of the respiratory infection, they must be healthy before being moved out of ISO and will need a veterinarian to examine them before they receive surgery, if they are not already altered.Behavior Observation:(4/7) Volunteer Observations -- Dog presented at the front of kennel and was easily leashed. Mellow was eager to leave the kennel and transitioned well through aisle/building. Dog pulls moderately on the leash and would benefit from a harness. Otherwise walks nicely on the leash. He has become more interested in socializing since last week, and solicits pets nicely. He accepts all over pets, enjoys being petted, and his body was loose while being handled. Mellow loves to play fetch. Handler used trade method, although Mellow did drop balls upon returning. Dog takes treats gently and knows "sit" command. Upon leaving play run, dog walked calmly back to kennel with handler. One volunteer positioned herself at the opposite side of kennel to encourage dog to move from front to back of kennel. Mellow entered kennel with no issue and immediately went to back of kennel to accept a treat. No issue with redirection.(3/24) Volunteer Eval -- Easy to leash used large loop and nylon leash as well based on previous history. Pulls on leash especially when he sees other dogs. Tense in run but did come up to take treats. Did not attempt further handling attempt gentle hind pets and small touches and had quick head turns. Did not attempt tag or toys. dog is TTA. Saw baby fire through fence and seems interested. Loose with tail wags. Pawed and cried through fence. Pulls towards dogs when walking. Evaled Blue/ (3/24) Per Lifesaving -- good when removing from kennel. Pulls on leash but walks well. Social outside and solicits attention from handler. Once back in the kennels dog stopped and did not want to walk back towards his kennel. With time, patience and treats got dog to walk back to his kennel. Handler put an orange nylon lead on the dog outside of his kennel and removed the slip lead. Put dog back in kennel with nylon lead, left the lead on and closed the kennel. Dog turned around and lunged while growling as kennel door was shutting. Otherwise he was kind, sweet and social - just doesn't like going back in his kennel. (3/10) Per Finder -- friendly, docile, protective already, chases cats - does not like cats!Per Foster Home:Here are some additional notes on my 4 days with Mellow. He seems to have some fear and past trauma around exiting the home. He is timid to go into the backyard and will only go out if I lead the way. He doesn't want to stay out long, returns to the door when he's ready. If he thinks I'm going inside without him he runs to the door. He is very enthusiastic about wanting to go for a walk, he sits in front of me and whines/barks when he wants to go out (even after he's just had a potty break in the backyard), he also jumps up at the front door. The doorbell is very alarming to him, he jumps up at the door, runs around, barks and whines. If he sees me going towards the front door he runs to the door. He follows the command "sit" but will not "stay". The second my hand touches the door handle he jumps up and charges towards the door. I tried to only open the door wide enough for me to slip through several times over the 3 days and he charged against the apartment door and pushed it open to escape into the common hallway. At that point he is extremely energized and wants to go outside, he does not listen verbal commands and growled/snapped when I tried to physically direct him with a gentle pull of his collar. I was only able to get him back inside by walking back inside myself until I was out of his line of sight, he would then follow. When he charged his way into the common hallway last night, I first tried verbal commands to get him back inside, when that didn't work I tried to put his harness and leash on, he growled, snapped and bit my leg. After I yelled "no" at him several times he stopped, froze and then followed my command to go into the apartment. He's broke the skin on my leg and it feels bruised. The remainder of the night he was calm and laid down by himself (not normal behavior - usually craves attention) and he only got up a few hours later to observe me cleaning up the kitchen and to follow me to the bedroom. On walks he pulls the entire time; he walks very fast with his nose down near the ground and zig zags from side to side on the sidewalk. He is mostly interested in sniffing all trees, grass, bushes. Other dogs catch his attention from 15-20' feet away and he pulls to greet them, but I have held him back and can redirect him within about 15 seconds. He pays n

animal.description: Re-introducing CINDER! Cinder came to us several years ago as a skinny stray and landed herself a foster home with her finder. Long story short, she was a bit full of herself back then and a couple of bites to the neighbor ended up with her being kicked out. Cinder previously attended doggy daycare where she basically would get along until she is overstimulated (which is what happened with the neighbor at the fence). Cinder entered our witness protection program and had been chilling and mellowing until now - we feel she is ready to try her hand at adoption. Once Cinder knows you she is rock solid. She has a job here at the rescue dog testing the new dogs - which makes her a VIP (Very Important Pup!). Cinder recently earned herself a Pen Pal (a buddy/mentor), Volunteer Caitlin - stay tuned for their adventures! Cinder is a champ at riding in the car and makes an excellent co-pilot. She is an easy walker and enjoys leisurely hikes. Good with dogs and great with cats. Cinder is a Shar Pei/Pit Bull mix and will turn 10 years old at the end of this month (April 2020). Let’s make 10 her lucky number! Cinder has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped and tested negative for heartworms and is on prevention. Adoption $150. Please fill out an application at www.companimals.org if you were interested in being Cinder’s happily-ever-after!

animal.description: **Update**  (1/10/21)  Paco & Polly have been in a foster home for a few months, but unfortunately it is not working.   Paco is a total sweetheart, and Polly is more dominant and is picking on another dog in their foster home.  Paco & Polly are very bonded and get along great together.  Due to some medical issues, they are not available for adoption.  We are looking for a permanent foster family for these two little ones.  IF YOU LIVE IN THE LEB/LANC/HBG AREA AND ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING PACO & POLLY, PLEASE EMAIL AngelsAmongUsRS@live.com  (4/25/2020)  Our newest AAU rescue family members....Paco & Polly! This sweet senior bonded pair are now homeless since their mom was sent to a nursing home, and they were surrendered to a shelter. Both are 11 years old,  Polly weighs 12 pounds, Paco 6 lbs. Both are friendly with people, but were understandably frightened in the shelter.   Paco & Pollly will be coming to AAU this week and will go directly to one of our wonderful AAU foster homes.   We are looking for a family who will welcome both of these little sweeties into their home since we will not separate a bonded pair.   IF YOU WOULD LIKE TO MEET THEM, PLEASE EMAIL AngelsAmongUsRS@live.com.

Mia is an owner surrender whom needs a patient and calm home, she does come out of her shell beautifully with spunky energy once acclimated to a new home. She loves to chase the squirrels out of the yard, play with her stuffies and lean on her humans. animal.description:
Watching 2-year-old Handsome stride about the bark park is an event filled with beauty and inspiration. At times, he moves with the equestrian canter gait so eloquently performed by a Tennessee Walking Horse. He also effortlessly glides along so smoothly that his motion appears to be a lighter-than-air phenomenon. Handsome will sometimes pause and gaze at you with a “what, me worry?” play-posture pose that is light-hearted, fun-loving, and peaceful. This is all even more amazing when you know of the experience of his past. Handsome arrived at the Humane Society as a feral canine who had never had the opportunity for even limited human interaction. It has taken a tremendous amount of care, kindness and all the loving energies of the Humane Society volunteers to help him learn how to live in the world of the humans, without fear and suspicion. He is a shy, quiet, gentle natured creature who is learning to trust and is becoming more confident, more comfortable, and more accepting of living the life of a canine who will be a cherished forever friend accompanied by a human who will share the bonding, companionship and unconditional love that makes life on this planet truly exceptional.
Handsome has spent some time with a loving foster family and has been the ‘father figure” for over a dozen puppies that have shared his temporary home. His capacities to care and nurture are everything that a human could ever hope to emulate. This special canine has an extraordinary gift that is both inspirational and inspiring. If you are hoping for a companion canine for one of your best forever friends, he is waiting and hoping. Handsome is fully house-trained and excels at communication and rapport with all ages and genders of humans. This is one special canine.

animal.description: PANEER - A44203608Intake Type: StrayDog Meets:Paneer and Makhani -- https://youtu.be/fL6G8UTNjA4Tandoori and Paneer -- https://youtu.be/jLRr0Db6E2AMedical Observation: (4/28) Vet Check -- On walk through patient was sniffing something in kennel and only lifted head when called out to him. Walked over to kennel door with loose body language and lightly wagging tail, pupils remained normal size (not dilated) and leaned into gate for some butt scratches. No hard barking, no jumping on kennel door or shying away from interaction. Trazodone not indicated at this time, but recommend continuing to monitor behavior.(4/25) Vet Check -- Patient is underweight, but otherwise appears healthy on examination. Patient's fever resolved (Fever at intake of 104.4)- suspect due to excitement. Dirty coat. Healed pressure sores over bony prominences. Behavior Observation: (4/26) Approached the front of the kennel with a slightly tense body, ears back, tail down. Slightly hesitant of the leash but would allow petting of the face and neck, eventually allowed leashing. Pulls moderate on leash. Urinates and defecates outside. Approaches handler with slightly tense body, accepts petting but does not solicit. Easily goes back into kennel.(4/25) Vet Staff -- Very friendly but head shy(4/25) Social at front of kennel when first approached, but retreated slightly when door was opened. When leash was presented, dog then went back to bed and laid down, adverting eye contact. While laying down, dog was able to be looped with sliplead but showed no interest in standing up or exiting kennel. Upon presenting treats, dog then eagerly stood up and came forward to both take treats from hand and eat ones that had been dropped. Able to continue to exit with lured treats but then became overwhelmed when other dogs from kennels began barking. Dog was then allowed to retreat back into kennel, treats dropped, and leash removed with no issues.This animal is currently available through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for you visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description:
All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Appointments can be made by calling 334-508-2367 or emailing troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

Beautiful ALDO deserves a chance in a solid loving Furever Home! He's a big goofy, playful guy!  Aldo is a BIG boy - 2  1/2 years old, 80lbs of lovin' - loves to play fetch and will jump thru a hoop to entertain you. We really prefer a home with a nice fenced yard for this dude. He is available for Foster to Adopt. Adopt donations would be $150, Older teens in the home will be considered.

With slow respectful intro Aldo could work with large breed dogs. He's neutered and will be up to date on all shots when placed. We will consider a Foster to Adopt placement with the right person. Aldo deserves his chance in a loving Furever Home NOW. We will assist the training if necessary with some assistance from his person.

Aldo is house-trained and crate trained. We prefer a stay-at-home person with minimal crate exposure and a nice fenced yard for Aldo to work off his young dog energy.

We are seeking an experienced dog person who will nurture Aldo, develop trust and love over time, while giving a young energetic playful dog a chance to get his feet 'set'.

Please contact us - GFStrays - cell: 862-200-1288, dogsrescuenow@gmail.com. We will contact you immediately.

animal.description:
Date of birth: 4/2019

12/17/2020: How adorable is this little Pit Bull mix?!! Kennedy is a year old and weighs 40 lbs. She is bright, cuddly, super sweet and she loves attention. She loves people.

• When Kennedy arrived at our shelter as a stray puppy, the poor little girl had a hip injury and needed FHO surgery. Sadly, she is still not 100 % even after the surgery, and still has some pain. She’s on Gabapentin daily to help with pain management, and Duralactin as a joint supplement to try to prevent the pain from becoming severe.  

• Kennedy was in foster care over quite a few months, which has been very helpful in giving us a picture of what type of home she needs. She needs a home with:

• someone who has dog experience and is dog savvy
• a house with a fenced yard
• no kids

• Kennedy plays well in doggie day care and playgroups. She’s a bossy and spicy player and can more than hold her own with other dogs!  She enjoys playing but because of her injuries she doesn’t play for long periods of time.  

• Kennedy has displayed some resource guarding in the form of bones and high value food.  

• She has lived with other dogs with mixed results due to her resource guarding and pain level. We think she could get along well with a dog who is happy-go-lucky and rolls with things if she gets cranky because of her pain.  If you have a dog, we can chat with you more and if Kennedy may be a good match, you could bring your dog to meet Kennedy. 

• She loves to go for walks and walks nicely on a leash. Our volunteers love to walk her!  She goes for 1.3 mile walks in pack walks.  She loves chewing on nylabones and playing with balls.  She rides nicely in the car.

• She can be a little nippy when she’s excited. She’s just playing, but she needs some work on that. 

• The poor girl has been through so much and is such a young dog. She needs a special home, but we know she’ll do great in the right environment and be a wonderful companion.! She's very loving and just needs a chance. Kennedy has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms. 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
http://hsgkc.org

animal.description:
If interested in adopting Buddah- please submit the adoption application found at this link-
https://form.jotform.com/51277873901158
Or at www.fetchafriendrescue.org
Please do not show up without an appointment and approved application. All dog visiting is by appointment only.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS:
-Primary applicants must be 21 or older and provide photo ID upon adoption
-Please read through a dogs entire bio before applying so you know that you fit the specific needs and requirements for that dogs new home,
-Dogs living in the home currently that are over 8 months old must be spayed/neutered unless medically unable.
-Please do not apply for a dog if you are unable to adopt within a week. We are unable to hold dogs due to our small size. Dogs coming into us are coming from local shelters that are euthanizing for space so holding a dog for an extended period does not allow another dog to be saved. 

AGE: 3-4 Years
SEX: Neutered Male
WEIGHT: 70 Pounds
BREED: Lab/Pitbull Mix
CAN LIVE WITH DOGS: No- I don't like to share my toys. And toys are a must have in my new home!! Play dates and going to doggy daycare would be really great though!
CAN LIVE WITH CATS: Yes
CAN LIVE WITH KIDS: 8 and up
DIET: Purina Pro Plan Chicken And Rice
FENCED YARD REQUIRED: YES chain link or solid - no invisible fences
ABOUT: Buddah is the best boy! He arrived to us back in November 2019 transferred from another shelter in South Carolina where he was found as a skinny stray. When he arrived we immediately noticed a terrible smell coming from his mouth. Assuming he had a bad tooth, he went to the vet to have things checked out and they discovered an old piece of wood was stuck to the roof of his mouth and had rotted in there. He required surgery to remove it, and during the surgery it was discovered that the infection had eaten two holes through the roof of his mouth and two teeth. These holes are not easy to close and he has had surgery each month since last December to try to repair the holes. After many months of healing Buddah is finally ready for his forever home! The holes could not be completely closed due to their size and how hard it is for them to heal. He has two small holes remaining but they do not affect his life in any way.
Despite his multiple surgeries and vet trips- Buddah LOVES going to the vet! He would race in the door and hop onto the exam table with his tail wagging so hard non stop and kissing everyone he saw. He adores every human he meets, and always left the vet with a new toy from the staff!
Buddah absolutely LOVES his stuffed toys! He does not chew them up and prefers to cuddle them or suck on them. His adoption even comes with his toy box FULL of toys that he has been acquiring since he arrived! He literally comes with a suitcase of his things! (bed, toys, treats, bowls, clothes-he loves wearing shirts!)
Buddah is housebroken, crate trained, and although hes the most perfect boy we have ever had- he is also one of the most stubborn. He requires a home with a fenced yard as he does not always come when called. If he doesn't want to go where you tell him he will sit down in protest and not move. Buddah deserves a home with a nice large yard to race around in.
Although he loves other dogs and has many friends- he will need to be the only dog in the home as he does not wish to share his prized toys with them. He goes to daycare regularly and is great with dogs of all sizes, and loves going for walks with other dogs. So he would be great fit play dates and outings with friends! He just simply does not wish to live with one.
Buddah knows his basic commands, walks great on a leash, loves to go for car rides and trips to the pet store! Buddah loves meeting people and going on walks with them. He is literally everyone's favorite dog and everyone knows him everywhere! Buddah is an active playful boy who goes for 5 mile walks a few days a week. He loves to play like crazy! But when hes done he naps and snuggles hard.
He is truly the perfect gentleman looking for the absolute best home ever where he will be spoiled and loved beyond belief! He knows his name very well and it suits him 100%! Buddah has an enormous fan club and deserves his own social media page for his fans to follow. He’s won many many hearts all over. He even had a a T-shirt designed with his face on it! He is looking for the best parents who will be “extra” and spoil him everyday as he is used to.
His adoption will not be first come first serve. Due to this best boys popularity- we will be accepting a certain number of applications and be selecting the best home for him. Let us know why you think you would be the best choice for Buddah. Buddahs new home will allow him to be on furniture, and will never use a shock collar or prong collar on him. He walks amazingly on a harness and does not pull at all. He is looking for a home that does not rent as his next home will be his last. Owners with prior dog owning experience is also preferred.
Buddah is neutered, heart worm negative, micro chipped, current on vaccinations and parasite prevention's!
ADOPTION FEE: $300

animal.description:
Zeus is a big mush of a dog of about 5 years old that just needs a good, safe home to spend his life in. If you can give him that, he'll give you all the love and loyalty you could ever hope for! Zeus was turned in because he continuously got out of his backyard, which resulted in altercations with a neighbor's dog. Poor Zeus was so scared when he arrived and just sat in his corner and trembled. But with lots of attention and encouragement, he came straight out of his shell and never looked back. He's such a good boy that is loving, sweet, smart, and well-behaved. He sits instantly and offers a pawshake when asked, he's housebroken and walks well on a leash. He just needs a home with a secure fenced yard and since he can climb a fence, he will need to have a leash on him in the yard. Zeus needs a home with no other pets but he sure loves people of all ages. He's such a doll that will bring lots of fun and happiness to a good family! File#29506 3/27/20 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Zeus.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

Name: Martin
Breed: Lhasa Apso
Age: 6 years old
Size: Small 
Pets: No
Kids: No
Ideal Home: One person. Adult only.
***Restrictions Apply/Special Needs*** 
Yes, we know he's a cutie, but this adorable face isn't what's going to get Martin adopted. Martin is in need of the right owner and home. Martin can be a bit quirky at times as he has resource guarding and is timid of new situations and people, especially men. Martin must go to a one person adult only home, with no other pets. Only dog owners with previous resource guarding and dog anxiety experience should apply.
 Martin will need patience, reassurance, and time to warm up to his adopter. Due to Martin's hesitation of new people, Martin's team requires qualified adopters to at a minimum come down to MHS to visit Martin twice a week, multiple times so Martin can build his trust and form a bond. Once he does Martin can be a complete cuddle bug who loves to play with squeaker toys, tennis balls, and enjoys a good belly rub. Martin enjoys lounging in the sun catching some rays, a nice long walk, and spending quality time with his people.
Martin is microchipped, neutered, and up to date on his shots. If you can commit to giving Martin the life he deserves please apply today.

Located at ACCT Philly, 111 W Hunting Park Avenue, Philadelphia PA !!!SOZAY - A42867462Intake Type:(3/28/2020) Return Adoption, (10/1/2019) StrayDog Meets:Sozay and Koala: https://youtu.be/mzVMmuC0UiMSozay, Candy Cane and Koala: https://youtu.be/MzSSt_Db6hASozay and Ruth: https://youtu.be/BaNzpfb9VYAVideos:Sozay dunking his head in the water bucket: https://youtu.be/lgbeezEteoEVideo:Very Good Boy SOZAY knows all the tricks! -- https://youtu.be/kD4KfjpvVq0Photos: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmMpuiyLWeight: 71lbsMedical Observation:(4/1) Vet Check -- Dog visualized having blood in kennel walls, distal end of tail tip observed to have blood on it ("happy tail"). Behavior Observation: (412) Pulls hard on leash, showed very little interest in toys, engaged slightly with assessor. Allowed handling with a loose body. Walked on leash and pulling subsided slightly. He began leash biting as we started to enter the building. Did not respond to treats but saw a KA and dropped the leash.(4/1/20) Per Vet Staff -- Animals behavior precludes actually PE(10/20/19) Volunteer Note -- Easy to leash and remove from kennel. Harnessed. Went into play yard, after leash was dropped, Sozay picked up leash and began playing with it. Was able to redirect with cheese and "sit". When tried to leave run, began leash biting: tug-o-war all the way from yard to kennel. At one moment saw dog and dropped leash, but then continued leash biting. KA came to assist, the presence of another person distracted Sozay and he dropped the leash.+Bite Details+Dog lives in owner's garage. Dog is chained when people are in and working in the garage. It was the end of the day and the owner unchained the dog because they do that at the end of the workday, when no one is in the garage. Owner opened door that connected the office to the garage, dog was behind door as owner opened it and then the dog jumped and started attacking owner's left side. Dog did not draw blood because owner was wearing a vest so dog only chewed through the vest. Owner twisted his vest / jacket off and left the garage. Owner's friend was still in the room with the dog and was trying to close the door that the owner originally opened. The dog jumped and bit friends left forearm.Was able to speak to owner. While owner did not have photos, the bite as described to me sounds like a level 3. Incident was a single bite with no deep punctures and lacerations were only extended due to owner pulling Sozay back.

animal.description:
Rowdy has been with us for some time and he remains a very sweet active boy.

Are you looking for a partner to go hiking? What about a run? A good game of soccer? Maybe a good movie on the couch? Rowdy could be the one for you!
A corgi-mix, Rowdy was picked up as a stray in SE Kansas shelter where Corgi Connection of Kansas got him. We estimate him to be around 3 years old.

He's a big boy at 40 pounds but very friendly. He's doing well with his foster brother, another large corgi. He has also done well meeting other dogs such as a golden retriever. Rowdy just loves to be on the go, but yet will also settle down. He needs some basic obedience training such as leash walking and recall work but he is catching on well. He does well in the house and has a super soft coat.

Must have: Large fenced yard; active owner; no young children just because he might knock them down unintentionally and unfortunately absolutely NO CATS.

Rowdy has been neutered, vaccinated and is micro-chipped. He's also on heart-worm and flea/tick preventative. His adoption fee is $275. If you are interested in this handsome boy, please submit an application through our website.

This dog is currently being fostered in Arkansas City, KS. CCK does adopt out of state but will NOT fly its dogs.

GERTRUDE - A#43774406Foster's Email: lcfaykes@gmail.comPhotos and Video: Gertrude! - https://flic.kr/s/aHsmLimngLGertrude in foster - https://photos.app.goo.gl/BRtyzR7CZ4nn4faP9Dog meets:Gertrude and Mr. Fantastic - https://youtu.be/-5UAqnJZZS0Jerry and Gertrude - https://youtu.be/CzLnJI0P--IAnderson and Gertrude - https://youtu.be/9ZXGmetaTjoPassion and Gertrude - https://youtu.be/K5fZHvLvXz8Robbie and Gertrude - https://youtu.be/-Chi_gsum6IBaby Smoke and Gertrude - https://youtu.be/G8201f0y45wBaby Smoke and Gertrude 2 - https://youtu.be/MNz0bcuGkZwGertrude, Manchego and Chip aka Ace - https://youtu.be/VTGiVDba0scHi, there. My name is Gertrude, but everyone just calls me Gigi. I'm 2 years old, I weigh an athletic 60 lbs, and I'm on the lookout for my forever home. Since you stopped by, I'd like to tell you a bit about who I am and the home I need to help me be the best girl I can be. My ideal person (or people) would have had a dog or two like me in the past, and will know how to help me shine. Most importantly you should know that I really like the calm and quiet setting I am in now in foster care, so having a lot of neighbors (like in an apartment building or townhouse) or a lot of visitors over often won't really work for me. Honestly, I want to be your one and only - kid, dog, or cat roommates don't fit that vision. I know that's a lot to ask, but in return, I will shower you with love and attention! I can't get enough kisses and belly scratches from my foster fam. I thrive on the whole snuggling thing too. I have a little bit of FOMO when it comes to what my foster parents are doing, so sometimes I follow them around to see if I can lend a paw. But the rest of the day I just sleep on the couch, relaxing without a care in the world. I'm super into my routine! I sleep through the night, nap through the morning, get my exercise on in the afternoon, and then crash by 8:30 pm. Playing ball is my favorite exercise so a fenced in yard would be best for me. During play time I look all energetic at first, but the funny thing with me is that it doesn't last very long! I prefer to stay away from busy parks because they're usually too crowded for my liking. And I definitely prefer to stay away from squirrels, or rather I prefer they stay away from me. I'm get pretty excited when I experience new things (meeting new people, visiting new places, etc), so I will need someone with patience and the know-how to help me learn that not every new thing is something to get amped up about. But I'm smart, if I do say so myself! I love "school", aka training time, and I challenge myself to learn new things as quickly as possible. Since moving into my foster home, I've learned sit, down, "come here," and to go into my crate when asked. I'm also house and crate trained. I even learned to ring a bell to tell my foster fam that I need to go out, so I'm pretty proud of that! To top it off, I'm learning about gentle leaders and how they make going on a walk more enjoyable for everyone. One more thing - I hear my adoption fee is sponsored, so that means I can come home with you for free. And that's pretty great! If you'd like to learn more about me, please email my foster at lcfaykes@gmail.com or you can visit my IG @theycallme_gigi_Intake Type: (4/11) Return, (2/7) StrayWeight: 60.8 lbsBite Details: (4/11) Gertrude and her owner were walking by their fence, getting ready to go for a walk. Gertrude saw the other owner's dog and "like a light switch", went after the other dog. Dogs start to fight and owner tries to break up the fight, but he got bit on the right hand. Owner's neighbor jumped the fence and tried to help break up the fight. Owner informed me that the neighbor did not require hospitalization, said he had some scratches but he was bleeding. Owner's wife also tried breaking up the dog fight and she got bit on her finger. Both owner and wife went to urgent care, got cleaned up and were give antibiotics. Owner had the worst injuries out of everyone. Owner's other dog was hospitalized, needed stitches. Owner said that Gertrude "took a big chunk" out of other dog's back. Gertrude latched on the other dog.This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact adopt@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster.We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more!Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
**Lola is a courtesy listing. Please contact Laurithomson@yahoo.com for adoption information.**

Lola is an affectionate 3-year-old spayed female pit bull mix who was rescued from a high-intake public shelter and is eager to find her forever home. Weighing about 65 lbs, Lola is a sweet and silly girl who loves to meet new people. Her other favorite activities include cuddling, playing with squeaky toys (the squeakier, the better!), patrolling for squirrels, going for rides in the car, and playing tug-of-war. She is also really good at sleeping. Lola relishes being close to her human and is a bit of a homebody: her favorite place is at home with her people. When she was rescued and moved into a foster home, she was overwhelmed by unfamiliar noises and things. She has made huge progress, and is now more confident walking around the neighborhood and going on hikes. She will thrive in a forever home that will continue to provide her with patience and structure as she continues to push the horizons of her world and to feel more confident in different settings. Lola is housebroken, knows how to walk on a leash, and has learned a number of obedience skills in her foster home. She is treat motivated, and is a good student. Lola needs to be your one-and-only companion animal, at least until her new human(s) get to know her and build a relationship with her. With all of the love and attention she wants to bestow on her human(s), you won't need anyone else! We also think she should be in a home with adults and teenagers as she doesn't have experience yet around younger kids. Lola would appreciate being in a home with a fenced yard in which she can run around and play when not snoozing on a comfy dog bed at your feet. Lola is a funny, charismatic, and loyal girl who will be a devoted best friend in a home eager to welcome her.

Check out the hashtag #Lolaisalover for more images and video of Lola on Instagram.

Lola is spayed, microchipped, and current on vaccinations.

Adoption application, home check, and adoption donation apply.

Lola is a courtesy listing. Please contact Laurithomson@yahoo.com for adoption information.

animal.description:
Meet Diego. Diego and his brother Pugsley (see his listing) have been through a lot together. They are a bonded pair and we will not consider splitting them up.
At approximately eight years of age, these two buddies lost their person, and were left alone, but together, in their home. Luckily a family member cared for them there, but they needed a place to go, and quickly, as their house was being sold. 
We saw these two on a rescue page, and many people reached out to us, hoping we could help these sweet seniors find a safe place to stay. We just couldnt say no. Thanks to a very kind foster, we were able to take the boys in on very short notice.
Everyone who meets these two cant say enough about how sweet they are. This is what they're foster parents have to say about them:
Pugsley is an adorable Puggle who is easygoing and lovable. He favorite thing is belly rubs and of course food. He also enjoys going for walks which has helped him lose weight. There are times when he gets scared of going up long flights of stairs and even just with a couple stairs, he needs encouragement. He has the cutest teddy bear-like face and there are times he may get anxious and cry but can easily be calmed down with a belly rub or chin rub. Currently Pugsley takes Gabapentin twice a day and one other pill to help with his joints although he seems to be doing amazing. The pills go right into his food so it is easy. We have tried lowering the dose of the Gabapentin per the vet since he seems to be doing so well. He goes on long walks and runs around in the backyard. We describe him as the perfect dog who just wants love.

Diego is a feisty Pomeranian mix with great energy for his age and very smart. He likes to cuddle but can also be independent. Diego loves going out for walks but gets so excited that he barks a lot but it is only because he can't wait to get outside. Sometimes he bites his leash as if to walk himself. Ideally a fenced in backyard is good for him that is secure because he has been known to try and sneak out. He does not take any medication on a regular basis.

They get along 95% of the time and love to lay together on a dog bed or blanket on the floor. Pugsley loves to eat and tries to eat Diego's food when he finishes his own so it is important to monitor that. Diego also does not have a lot of teeth but can eat kibble and soft food where the chunks are cut into small pieces. They also both like cantaloupe and bananas. Diego also likes cucumbers cut in small pieces. Occasionally, Diego may have an accident in the house, but otherwise they are trained to go outside.

These two boys dont ask for much...just a loving, patient, cat -free home where they could finally settle into a routine and call someplace home again. They love to play in a fenced yard, and would prefer the company of mature humans...so an adult home, or one with understanding older children would be kindest.
 
Adopt double the love today with this bonded pair. Submit your application: https://www.hharteam.org/adoption-form/
Diego and Pugsley's adoption fee is $250 to a qualified adopter.

She just wants to be loved..and taught how to be a dog...a puppy still..and needs a patient owner.

animal.special_needs_notes:
Update 1.30.2021
She needs to be an only dog.. but she is very loving with people. Must have a fenced yard.. and NO apartments..this is not negotiable. Experienced owners only.

Update 9.11.2020 she has been with us 8 months and her Craniomandibular Osteopathy has absolutely no restrictions for her. She is not on meds, she is not in any pain, and she is slowly outgrowing the bone growth shift.  Please dont let this deter you..she is a sweetheart, she is smart, but she requires an experienced owner with an active bully.

UPDATE..4.22.2020 Lila has been with us for nearly 3 months ..she was closer to 7 months when she left Broward and she was showing signs of pain there but with us she didnt..she was on anti inflammatory meds but hasnt been on them either for some time. 

She eats hard kibble just fine.. requires hard toys.. stuffies don't stand a chance... she plays hard with our othet pocket bullies..loves to snuggle and is super spazzy but also incredibly sweet. 

We have had only one fever flare and that was remedied by meds. 

Please research Craniomandibular Osteopathy and see if you feel she is just as equally worth the chance we felt she deserved.  She can outage this!!

More about her personality in the bio section.


FROM THE SHELTER VETERINARIAN: prior to her arrival 

Lulu is only 6 months old but this sweet puppy appears to have a rare bone condition consistent with Craniomandibular 

A bone disorder of growing dogs, this condition causes oral discomfort, weight loss, fever, and palpable enlargement of the mandible. 
 
Lulu is still a young pup and we are hopeful that with medications to reduce inflammation and discomfort, along with a soft food diet, her prognosis will improve with time. 

It is a painful condition however, and although Lulu is currently on pain medication, she needs a rescue to help her get out of the shelter as soon as possible and provide continued management so that she has the chance to have a normal life.

He is a big, young guy (3 years old) and looks like he weighs close to 90 pounds. Scooby adores people. He loves belly rubs and getting treats. His eyes will melt your heart. He truly is the sweetest dog.
His biggest obstacle on getting out of the shelter is he can climb out of a 10 foot high chain link fence. He can jump a 5-6 foot fence easily and he will show you his skills if he sees another animal. Scooby is under the impression that all other animals are bad. He wants him and his people to be the only breathing things on his property.

Scooby needs training. He is smart and could be worked with. He is hoping someone with no other pets who happens to have an 8 foot high wooden fence and lives out in the country will be his hero. He doesn't want to live his life in a little boxed in kennel. He has too much love to give.
If you are willing to adopt him I bet our Castoff family on FB could raise the money to build a fence for him if that would help.
For more information, please call (706) 487-4539.

Age: 2 years
Weight: 75 lbs
Temperament: Gets along adults and teens.
Training: house-trained, Crate-trained, would benefit from basic training
Vetting: neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and heartworm negative
Contact adopt@doggieharmony.org with questions or complete/send an Adoption Application for fastest response. We look forward to hearing from you.
To ensure we're meeting both pet and adopters' needs, we ask potential adopters to complete an Adoption Application ( www.bit.ly/DH-Adoption ) for caretakers to review. animal.description:
Hope was rescued from a Houston shelter at the very last minute!

When Austin Cats and Dogs Rescue was alerted, we quickly mobilized to find a foster home for her.  

She is safe and settling in after what was a very stressful experience of being sheltered, and being separated from her babies.

She shows signs that she was probably used for breeding, and was not socialized with a loving family in her previous life.

Our goal is to work with her in a foster home, or to place her with an adopter that is committed to giving her security, affection, and confidence that she will be safe and loved for the rest of her life.

Are you that person?  We will be selective in choosing a new home for Hope, because she does need work reaching her full potential.

She loves being with the other pets in her current foster home, and they are her bridge to developing a bond with the humans in the home.  She enjoys the structure and routine that she never had before.  It might be a must that her adopter have another well-socialized pet, as that would ease her in transitioning.

Hope is positive for heartworms, and will be treated at our expense.

**Potential adopters must be aware that at the present time Hope will not allow anyone to pet her or come near her, and she needs a lot of work.  She needs a patient family to work with her by feeding her right out of their hands, to assure her and to develop trust.

She will not let humans touch her, so she needs help in that area and, therefore, she cannot be leashed.  

She will have to stay in the house and in a secure backyard for a long time until she overcomes this fear.

She is nice and friendly, but doesn't want dogs or humans approacing her. Hope does not hurt anyone, but will bark if someone walks toward her. 

ATXcatsdogs@gmail.com is contact for potential fosters or adopters!

Pets are adopted to homes in the Austin, Texas, metro area, only.

For more photos and info:

Follow us on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/austincatsanddogsrescue/

Follow us on Instagram https://www.instagram.com/austin.catsanddogs.rescue

animal.description:
Odin is a now-healthy year old pup with a sense of adventure and curiosity about his surroundings. He came to RESCUEDohio as a very sick dog, with severe bone deformation and dental problems. After 4 surgeries and a long, painful recovery, his legs are mended and he's ready to play!

Because Odin has been cooped up in a crate, wearing a cone for most of his young life, and because he has only recently gained the use of his legs, he has been a very frustrated puppy. His frustrations come out through mouthiness. Odin will need to be kept in supply of durable chew toys as he loves to chew and is used to this activity as his only form of exercise. These days, Odin is free to walk on leash, play with other dogs, and fetch toys over a short distance. He is not a suitable companion for a runner, and should not be forced to run or do any extreme weight-bearing exercises.

Odin's mouthiness can come out in the form of resource guarding. His foster mom is teaching him "no" and he is learning that when he listens to her, he is rewarded with even better toys and treats than whatever it is he is guarding. Odin will need to live in a home with people who are experienced at dog training, to help reinforce good manners and set him up for a good experience in life. We do not recommend that Odin lives in a home with small children, as we do not want him to resource guard children's toys.

Odin has not been cat tested, but he is very dog friendly and has lived with both male and female dogs of all sizes and has wanted to play with all of them! In fact, he lives with his foster brother Buddy and they are best friends. They love to play chase and have wrestling matches in the backyard (check out his bio and consider adopting both!).

Odin has very specific needs and we will only consider applications that can give him what he needs to in his forever home. Odin will require a forever home with a fenced in yard. Odin's adoption fee is $300 and meet and greets can be arranged for approved adopters; apply today at rescuedohio.org!

animal.description:
We will not be showing dogs until Science Based Home restrictions are lifted for non-essential businesses but are reviewing applications for the best fit for each dog.

Diesel is a one of a kind dog. He is neutered, male that is approximately 2 years old (2020). He came to MAPS after he was pulled within hours of being euthanized at the shelter he came from. Diesel also had a bad case of “happy tail”, which is a cut at the end of the tail from whacking it hard on surfaces. It took many months to get DIesel’s happy tail to fully heal, and he was a good sport with the bandaging and treatment. 

Diesel is a great listener and knows sit and wait. He can hardly contain himself while he waits for a treat though and will bounce up and down while whining as if to say “I need that treat now.”  Diesel is a dog who has really come into his own since joining his foster home. He is one of the best walkers in the rescue. He will check in with his people, and does not pull hard; even when there are distractions. Diesel also enjoys playing fetch, and loves to show how athletic he is. He is able to catch balls on the move and is very coordinated. 

Diesel is a guy who will help provide purpose to your life. He will help you realize the importance of living in the moment, and looking beyond yourself.  He was given a second chance at life, and he can help you realize all the things we can be thankful for. Complete an application to begin the process toward starting a long, positive relationship with this special guy.

Application Process

MAPS’s adoption process is designed to help best place dogs with homes that are in the best interest of the dog and their human companions. The adoption process starts with a prescreen review of a Guardian Application. Making decisions about dog placement in adoptive homes is an "art", not a "science", and there will be times when applications will be denied for various reason(s). This is left to the discretion of the MAPS after reviewing relevant information. MAPS reserves the right to make all decisions regarding placement or final disposition of any rescued dog in its care into a foster or adoptive home. There is absolutely no guarantee, made or implied, that any person or persons requesting to adopt a dog being fostered through MAPS, or posted on MAP's web site, will be granted an adoption. After a successful prescreen, including background checks, the applicant(s) are notified that they can visit the dogs and a time slot is made for the dog and applicant interaction. After the interaction we encourage several days of reflection before adopting a pet to help assure this will be a lifetime commitment of love and quality care for the dog. Next we conduct a home/neighborhood visit to the Guardian Applicant's home. If the home visit proves successful the new mom and/or dad of the dog will sign an Adoption Agreement and share a lifetime of love and mindful growth !

Guardianship Application available for download at

http://tinyurl.com/MAPSFiles

MAPS Dog Rescue Mission

Midwest Area Pit Stop, Inc. (MAPS) is a foster home based rescue located in Madison, Wisconsin established in 2005 after being part of the Chicago Illinois based rescue Furry Friends for several years. MAPS focuses on providing a structured, safe calm environment for the dogs in their care that helps them flourish. This structured home environment is complimented by exercise, Positive Reinforcement Deference Training, very high quality dog food in addition to a broad spectrum of proven food supplements including vitamins and supplements. In addition to fostering, MAPS provides sponsorship funds to help with the veterinary expenses and/or Breed DNA testing to save dogs in need of a rescue at the end of their options. MAPS has been active in the community promoting dog safety, how to build a healthy relationship with your dog, and fighting breed discrimination including breed testing of hundreds of dogs since December 2007. MAPS believes that dogs are a central component for people to have a more meaningful and purposeful life. That is, if people are willing to embrace mindfulness in daily living. Dogs help us connect to reality and make life worth living through example and deep bonds. MAPS is not about how many dogs are adopted in the shortest amount of time but rather measures to help insure the dogs that are adopted do not come back for the wrong reasons.

animal.description:
Hey y'all, my name is Ousier. I'm part of the Steel Magnolias litter of pups, named after characters in the movie. German Shepherd/Pit bull mixes, born the first of May, and raring to go!! Sadly, the rescue has had no room at the inn for me and my sister as far as a foster home is concerned so we're still with our parents' owners. The rescue has gotten us fully vetted and will work with us on leash prior to adoption but we will still need an experienced adopter, preferably with a fenced in yard. We have had very little socialization or human contact in these first 7 months of life but each of our siblings are doing great now that they are in new homes. We aren't aggressive at all, we just need to be shown what's what. We don't know about toys or kisses and haven't been inside but are eager to learn about all that life has to offer once we feel safe in our new surroundings. With a little patience and understanding, we will both turn out to be loyal companions. We love other dogs and can be cat tested if need be, as we've never been around one. Due to our circumstances and age, we keep getting bypassed for typical bouncy youngsters. Please give me a chance, won't you?? 

If you are interested in giving me a forever home please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us we will be glad to help!

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Female Estimated Date of Birth: April 7, 2013 Size: 60 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING RUBY
Ruby came into Paulding County as a stray at the beginning of March 2020. They immediately noticed she had some unsteadiness. She has some moments of being totally fine and others where she is unsteady on her feet and falling over herself. She was still eating and drinking normally and even did well with other dogs through the kennel. Our friends at Paulding put out a rescue plea and one of our amazing previous adopters met her and agreed to foster! Ruby got her freedom ride on April 8, 2020.
ABOUT RUBY
Despite being a little off balance, Ruby is a complete wiggle-butt and warms up to people immediately. She has the sweetest demeanor and craves human affection! She is enjoying life in her foster home and gets along well with most other dogs, including her doggie foster-siblings. She completely ignores the resident cats and has zero prey drive outdoors. Initially her foster family thought she was just stubborn; however, much to their surprise, Ruby is actually deaf! She is a little slow to move around, but when she's excited, she can move a short distance. She loves wandering around the yard, but due to her deafness, Ruby has no concept of vehicle traffic and certainly will not come when called so she will need either a fenced yard or a family that is committed to always keeping her on leash. In almost all instances, Ruby's demeanor is very chill, although she is a rope-tug champion, will occasionally attacks pillows left in her reach, and sings when she's crated. Ruby is spoiled rotten and can't stand being away from her people, but when they leave the house, she simply takes up residence on the couch for a long nap (snoring like a hot rod motor!). She won't wake up when you get back since she can't hear you coming.
Ruby would love a family where she can live out her golden years. She most likely had a stroke or possibly some other neurological damage that causes the slight droop in her face and wobbly gate, but she's not one for activity anyway. She is a laid back, slow, stop and sniff the roses kind of gal. Ruby would do best in a home with minimal or no stairs.
Ruby is still heartworm positive and hasn't started treatment yet, but we have been addressing some skin issues that needed antibiotics first.
*Please check back for updates on this lucky lady*
Photo Album of Ruby: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=3068473496544129
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Incredibaly Smart!Roxy was born about May 6, 2018 and weighs about 30 lbs. She pretty much looks like a large Jack Russell, but we are just guessing at her breed. She came to us from a home with three kid and another older large dog who she would harass to play with her, but there was no interest. Roxy has a lot of energy and needs a person who will give her that release or another dog to really play with her and she's a bit on the rough side. Roxy has a TON of personality and she needs her new humans to be smarter than she is. I've learned that some dogs are so very smart that they are labeled as bad dogs which is what Roxy was labeled when she came here. Roxy had nipped a couple of the kid's friends when they entered the home or when running around. And then there was the UPS driver when she was on the electric fence...yes, it's true that some humans have an e fence for their dogs that INCLUDE the driveway - not been able to figure that one out. So, going forward she either needs a rural environment or a physical fence and an adult only home and when there are guests she should be crated or closed in a room. In the evening she is a major lap dog and soaks up the love. She lays among all the other dogs at the main site and all is good. She would run from her owners when they wanted to pick her up and just a bit ago I tried that and she did back away, so easy, peasy, I looped a leash, put it around her neck and drew her to me - no problem. This is not a horrible dog and thankfully she came here as she would not have walked out of most other shelters. Again, we need humans that are going to figure her out and enjoy the intelligence, the comedy, the energy, of this 30 pounds of dynamite and will keep her from injuring any humans. Roxy has a ZEST for life! The Adoption Fee for this dog is $300.00.
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description: I have started a new adventure! I have enrolled in what the hoomans call the Prison Program so I won't be available for awhile. I am learning how to be around lots of people and gaining confidence in my surroundings! Hello! My government name is Mini Milky, but my fosters renamed me Yeti. Im about 11 months old and about 40lbs now, but I still might have a little growing to do. Im very shy and wary of new people. It will take me awhile to warm up to you, so I need a forever home with VERY patient humans who will give me the time I need to feel comfortable while also pushing me outside of my comfort zone in healthy ways. I have a spunky personality and playful energy once Im out of my shell. Im quite silly, and I love to play with the other dogs in my house. I would probably do best in a home with one or two adult humans and one or two other dogs. Although I am afraid, I am not aggressive. I really like to have a consistent routine for my daily activities. A routine helps me settle and feel comfortable. My kennel is my favorite place to be because I feel safe there. I am kennel trained, know my name, and will tell you when I have to go potty once a routine is established. - Yeti From Yeti's Foster Mom: "Yeti is a happy, but scared 11 month old puppy. She is very talkative when she needs something and will let you know, i.e. when she needs to go potty. Yeti is a very smart, curious and capable pup that needs special attention and care from the right forever home. We have been fostering her for around 5 months and she is just starting to feel comfortable enough to let us pet her on her own terms. She has taken to one of the adults in our house more than the other, so shes probably more of a one person dog than a family dog. Full disclosure: Yeti is not your typical I-love-everyone puppy. She will spend the first few weeks figuring out your space and your routines. She will avoid you and your presence for a long while and needs someone patient and willing to work extensively with her to build trust. Yeti acts like a normal playful puppy around other dogs, but when humans come around she is very timid and scared." Yeti's adoption fee will be $375 which includes her spay, vaccinations and any additional medical care she may have needed.

animal.description: America is a sweet 12 year old Shepherd mix. She came to Labs and More needing some TLC and is recuperating in an experienced foster home. America is fostered with other dogs but wants her space from them. She likes to establish herself as top dog. She can be a bit particular in her old age and needs an adult only home. She likes her space when she eats both from other dogs and people, and she will need a home with prior dog experience. She is mellow and takes food from her hand gently. She is familiar with a leash and content with a few short walks each day. America is housetrained and will wait at an open door until she has permission to go outside. She is crate-trained and has no problem going in her kennel if you need her to. She also rides well in the car. If you're looking for a mellow, loyal senior dog to be your companion for the rest of their days, America may be the girl for you! animal.description: This spunky boy with lots of love to give is Ezra! He is about 3 years old and a mix of Boxer and Dutch Shepherd. Ezra landed at Labs and More after being diagnosed with a heart murmur. While he has been cleared for adoption by our vets, he will require daily medication that keeps his heart beating at a regular pace and it may increase as he gets older. Ezra is a happy boy who loves to be by your side. He loves to play with dog toys and tennis balls, and has a great time at Fiesta Island with his foster family! However, he will not be a running partner or be a candidate for extended bouts of exercise due to his medical needs. Puzzles, games and mental exercises would be great ways to mentally challenge this smarty pants and wear him out. Ezra can be choosy with his dog friends but when he can social distance like at Fiesta Island, he does fine. He thinks kitties are for chasing and would do better in home with no children or children over the age of 10. Ezra is house trained and he needs a forever family that understands his condition and is willing and able to work with it to give him a happy and loved life. If you are interested in meeting Ezra, your first step is to submit an adoption application on our website today! animal.description:
Hello friends! My name is Cali and I am a shy girl looking for my own person to love! 
I arrived at the shelter in the middle of winter under the most dire of circumstances…let’s just say I found myself without a home (through no fault of my own) and am so thankful that the Marshmallow Shelter was able to welcome me with open arms!  I am very shy and reserved until I get to know and trust you…then I show you my silly side! My ideal home would have: 
-Previous dog experience as an adult (having a dog as a kid does not count). I will need someone that can help grow my confidence. 
-Patience – I will need you to go slow with everything so I feel at ease with all the new excitement! 
-No kitties – maybe another dog but I would prefer to be the focus of your attention at least for a while so we can bond!
-Older kids only so everyone can participate in things such as training. I’m also quite large and might accidentally knock down the little ones!
-A home with a fenced yard would be AWESOME so we could play together.  

Apply online to learn more about me! www.marshmallowfoundation.org
Visitors to the shelter are by appointment only and after an application has been submitted online.

animal.description: Whitley is an Australian Cattle Dog of about 5 years and 50lbs. He needs a very heeler-savvy leader as his person. Whitley is very loyal and a total velcro dog to his people. People are his favorite, other dogs are his least favorite. He may have been attacked when he was younger which, in combination with a very dominant personality, leads him to be reactive to other dogs. He needs a home with a fenced back yard since he can't enjoy any other typical off-leash spots for dogs like dogs parks and doggy day cares. Whitley is very intense, is easily excitable and needs a home that wants to provide him a moderate-to-high amount of activity. Since he is food motivated, he is a great trainee and wants to please! Whitley is a typical velcro dog and wants to be by your side, always. He loves his person and just wants to find his forever companionship in a human. His ideal home is with his humans and no other dogs or a submissive dog. He is house trained and a total dream in the crate. He knows sit, down and shake. Whitley is neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and preventives, microchipped and heartworm-negative.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

PLEASE NOTE: GPMR communicates primarily by email. If you have any questions regarding one of our Mastiffs, please read their bio and if you still have questions- drop us an email at info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.org . If you have questions about our adoption procedures, please go to our Pages of Interest on the left hand column under 'Adoption Info.' We answer email inquiries almost immediately-usually always within a few hours and phone calls are returned with 24-36 hours.

GPMR does not have a shelter. All of our dogs are kept in loving foster homes. We must have a completed adoption
application on file before meeting any of our mastiffs.

GPMR adopts to the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana and parts of Colorado.
!!!Any mastiffs being adopted out of the state of Oklahoma require a health certificate to be paid for by the adopter!!!

Willow is part of our 'Fall in Love' adoption special and has a reduced adoption fee of $225.Meet Willow! She came into GPMR when her owner had to go through cancer treatment and wasn't able to keep her. She lived with that family since a puppy and she was terrified and confused when she first arrived into rescue. We don't think she was mistreated at all but it's clear she never left her home very much and so new situations are very scary for her. She gets so scared that she will urinate in fear at the vet's office, which makes us feel so bad for her.Willow is almost 5 years old. She is great with other dogs but does not like to share her food bowl, so she just needs to be fed by herself. Other than that she does great, and is curious about cats but not enough to investigate. The ideal home for Willow would be a quiet, adult only home, she is scared of children and the noises that come along with having little ones. Willow's family needs to patient with her and understand that she will take several weeks to adjust in her new home. She loves her crate and that's where she goes when she is worried about something. She is house trained as well and is very well behaved indoors. When she goes outside she likes to do her business and come right back inside. She is definitely a homebody and not a good match for someone who wants a Mastiff they can bring places with them. She much prefers to be home rather than out and about.Willow was adopted to a single woman and then returned 8 months later when the woman developed health issues and was no longer able to care for Willow. We were so sad for both of them! Since Willow has been back, she's done really well adjusting back into her foster home. We're proud that she was able to go to a new home and then come back, without having any major setbacks. We know her forever home is out there!Willow was recently diagnosed with partially torn ACL's in both knees. One side has been like that a while and the specialist said likely injured it long before we got her. The other side is a recent injury and we've opted to try a brace on the knee instead of surgery. It should arrive soon and from talking with other Mastiff owners, they've seen really good results with it.Willow is being fostered in Guthrie, OK.Save a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description:
Hey there, it’s Polar! Yes, I’m back with Moonsong. You might remember my story, I came a loooong distance to Moonsong from a shelter in Alabama back in 2018.  You see I had tested positive for heart worm and none of the rescues in that area had room for me. Lucky for me Moonsong didn’t let me down, they sent their amazing volunteer who they call Superman to my rescue!  He drove many, many miles to come save me and transported me to Wyoming and then I hitched a ride to Boise, Idaho.    What a journey!  And the great news is my heart worm treatment was successful, so I’m just on a routine preventive.

I got adopted to a nice lady and move to Oregon for a bit. I loved my time in my new home. Unfortunately, my prey drive got the better of me and I got into a bit of trouble. Because of my prey drive, absolutely no home with cats, small dogs or other small pets will be an option for me. 

Being a teenager, I’m a high energy boy and like to pull and be out front on walks. I’m learning about loose leash walking, impulse control and lots of other fun stuff with the force free trainers who work with me. I know basic commands like how to sit and lay down. I’m pretty easy to train because I LOVE food! I’m really strong and would love to learn how to skijor and bikejor. I just need a little training. My perfect family is active and would continue my force free training.

I get super excited when I see other dogs during walks – I just want to go meet them! I have been in play groups in the past and I really liked that! With careful introductions I get along with the other dogs my size and just ignore anyone trying to start trouble.

I am house-trained and have been told that I’m like a cat because I love attention and close contact. I can be a big lap dog! If you’re up for adopting a sweet, active, handsome Malamute, please get in touch with my “agent” below!

Note: Because Polar is leash reactive, his owner must have the physical strength to manage him.  Polar needs a family with previous experience with Malamutes that is willing to take the time to continue his force free training.

animal.description:
Look at this beautiful girl! This is Mia. Mia is a Boxer and American Staffordshire Terrier mix. Mia is around 2 years old. She was dumped off in a busy park and left to fend for herself. She kept running up to people wanting to play. She's very friendly and loving. One of our foster mom's neighbors saw her and offered Mia a ride. Mia was more than happy to accept and jumped into the car and off they went. :) The neighbor rode around trying to find her owners but with no luck. She was taken to the vet and scanned for a microchip but there was none. She was reported to the shelter and posted in all of the lost and found groups yet no one came forward. We can't imagine why because this girl is a total sweetheart!

We are now trying to find a forever home for Mia. Mia weighs 52 lbs. She is awesome with people and other dogs. She has lots of energy and loves to run and play. She can also be relaxed and calm. Mia would do best in a home with children 10 years old and older. She would do great in a home that has another dog that likes to play. She would do great in an active household. She must go to a home with a fenced in yard. Mia would be an awesome addition to any family.

If you are interested in adopting Mia please email fureverangels@aol.com for an application.

animal.description: All we can think when we look at Angus is, GAH!! How can a dog be this cute?! That wrinkled face, the smooshy lips, the sneaky side-eye... it's all too adorable! Angus is one of those dogs who thrives once he has some consistency and guidance. When he first arrived at the shelter, he was so afraid that he would hide under his bed. But after lots of positive interactions, Angus learned that the staff and volunteers were there to help him and take care of him. He definitely has his enthusiastic moments but he calms with appropriate redirection, and focus games are his jam! Angus loves toys and one of his favorite things to do is select a toy from the toy bin and then throw it around in the air. Yippee! Angus is always super excited to make friends. Hey new person, are you my fren? Yes! What about you, mister, you my fren, too? Ok! And that person over there not looking at me, can they also be my fren? Yay! Angus is also very dog social and enjoyed going to play group at the shelter. We think he would love to live with a doggy friend, or go on regular play dates! We know from his time in foster that Angus is house trained and crate trained. He walks nicely on a leash and wants to sniff allllll the things! Angus is still a youngin so he sometimes decides to chew on stuff he is not supposed to, but he trades nicely for a treat or an appropriate toy. Angus would do well in most home environments but we would not recommend young kiddos since he can sometimes get jumpy/mouthy when he is excited. I weigh approximately 57 lbs.
