animal.description:
MINA

Mina is  a Shepard Mix, born 1/21/18. She is VERY active so not a good match for small children. She would benefit greatly with a training class with OUR trainer which we will provide.

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Mina or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description:
Torta is a 6 year old female Pekingese rescued from a puppy mill.
She has been terrified of her own shadow for a long time. She loves to run around outside with all the dogs and bark at birds and the others but human touch is not something she enjoys. She has been groomed but wasn't an easy task. We are holding her every single day like it or not and believe she is coming around to love. We have finally seen the crowning glory of her tail coming up and curling over her back. She goes potty outside and has used a potty pad inside.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description: Maeve is a sweet blind senior girl who got lost prior to the quarantine. She wandered around in a rainstorm before she was picked up and taken to a high kill shelter. The rain washed away all the familiar scents and she was unable to navigate home. Poor little thing waited for her family to save her, but no one ever came. We rescued Maeve and had her examined by our vet. She has a heart murmur, and the vet started her on medication. Maeve is a very loving little dog, loves to cuddle and sit by your side. Although she is blind, she quickly learned her foster mom's home and yard and navigates just fine. We believe she can still see light and dark. Maeve is happy, friendly and very devoted. She would be the perfect dog for someone who is lonely or retired. Maeve gets along well with her foster siblings, is house triained, spayed and fully vaccinated. Maeve would love to spend her golden years in a loving safe home. Adopting a senior dog is one of the most rewarding things you can do. They are so grateful and shower you with love. These amazing dogs deserved better than the lives they had before, and you can make a difference! If you live in the Los Angeles area, please complete our adoption application found on dexterfoundation.com

animal.description:
Meet Bubba!  
Bubba is approximately a 2 year old neutered mix of a boy! The most popular guesses have been Boxer, English bulldog, mastiff, rottie combinations.  DNA results are pending so time will soon tell!  For now we just know he is a cutie!  Check out the pics and his nubby tail video to see for yourself!
In Bubba’s short life he has spent several months in a shelter only to be adopted and returned 2 different times.  While Bubba LOVES being with his people, he doesn’t really care for people in his personal space.  He is a bossy boy who likes to take charge and can sometimes be rude and demanding.  If Bubba doesn’t want to do something or doesn’t like you doing something he will let you know it.  Sometimes that means jumping on you, sometimes that means being mouthy and/or pawing at you.   Bubba needs a calm, confident, strong leader who is willing to love him, give him personal space and establish boundaries for acceptable behavior.  Bubba needs to be trained to understand he is NOT in charge and it is NOT OK to jump and/or be mouthy.
Bubba is a super star in his crate.  He sits calmly, does not bark and will willingly “go to his house” any time he is instructed to do so.  He loves toys!  Plush toys, chew toys, rope toys, bone toys…any toy will do and Bubba does a great job entertaining himself with his very large toy collection.  Bubba is already potty trained, crate trained, and sits perfectly for his treats and will sit and wait for his food. 
The ideal home for Bubba would be a low traffic home with adults who are willing to love and spend time with him while giving him personal space to be his happiest.    Because Bubba is so bossy, he will need an adopter who understands this and is willing to establish and continuously reinforce boundaries of acceptable behavior to help Bubba succeed.   We know Bubba will be a great companion for the right person/people.  We believe in Bubba so much that we have fully funded a contract with a trainer to help Bubba and his future foster/adopter adjust to a new life together.  Bubba will need to be a single dog and is not a fan of kitties.
If you are interested in adopting Bubba please visit www.zoeshouserescue.com and complete an application.   His adoption donation is $350

animal.description:
Carmelo came to us terrified of everything, and is in a foster learning to feel safe. It is going well but will take some time. She is not ready for adoption yet, but we wanted to keep her on the page to share her journey.

Day 1 (April 10): Carmelo arrives at her foster home and her kennel is set up inside of a pen - her own safe spot to unwind without interference.

Day 2 (April 11): Carmelo ventured out overnight for a meal. Today she stuck her front bits out for kibble and water. She also played subtle peek a boo with her foster mom through her cage door. Those ears! Have you ever seen a grander pair?

Day 3 (April 13): She finally shows herself! Not for long. but more than yesterday. And her foster mom got to pet her a little inside her crate. She's ever watchful through those holes in the side.

Day 4 (April 14): Carmelo's foster mama thinks this new arrangement is great! It gives Carmelo a more open view of life outside the crate (which involves lots of harmless animal love). She's not as sure. Her foster mom shut the crate but didn't lock it and Carmelo seemed to relax some. Plus Carmelo will feel independent when she pushes it open. In theory anyway!

Day 5 (April 15): Little sweetness made it out of her crate. She still doesn't want to be touched. But at least she's out watching her foster family (her foster mom, mostly). She's still matching the appetite of a dog much larger than herself - the poor thing must have been starved.

Progress every day. We can't wait until she trusts her foster mom enough to come out and interact! We'll let you know when the time comes!

If interested in Carmelo, please complete our application at our website here: https://lastchanceatlife.org/adoptable-pets/dog-adoption-application/ 1/30/21 10:58 PM

animal.description:
** Please read the bio in its entirety before emailing with questions or submitting an application**

DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS, MESSAGES ASKING QUESTIONS THAT ARE ANSWERED IN THE BIO WILL NOT RECEIVE A RESPONSE. ALL DOGS LISTED ARE AVAILABLE.

Look at this beautiful boy! Buford is a Parvo survivor (no worries about him ever getting it a second time!) who is now healthy and looking for his forever home.

Buford is a year old, approximately 20 lbs, and okay with most dogs (although he prefers female dogs and does not like large male dogs) and cats.

He's a little shy when he meets new people but he takes just a minute or two to warm up and then he's ready to be your buddy. He's got lots of energy, but is also a snuggler. Buford would be fine in a home with a dog friend (he's fine tolerating most other dogs but is unlikely to be a play mate to another dog), or would be just as happy being showered with all of the attention.

* Just turned a year old

* Neutered, vaccinated, micro chipped and UTD on both flea and heartworm prevention.

* Not recommended for a home with children

* Does not like large male dogs

* Okay with dog savvy cats but tends to bully cats who are less dog savvy.

* Adopters must live within 2 hours of Florence, KY. Unfortunately, we cannot make exceptions

* $212.00 Adoption fee

** Not appropriate for a home that shares walls with neighbors (no apartments or condos)

His listing will be removed as soon as he has an approved application

If you have specific needs that aren't addressed in the bio (children in the home, small animals, apartment/condo living, etc) please email to ask if the dog is suitable for the environment before submitting an application. Once the application is submitted, please expect someone to email you with questions and/or provide more information about the dog is we are unsure that the dog may be a good fit.

Most importantly, please be honest! We have many people tell us what they think we want to read, not what's truthful. If there are discrepancies, your application will be denied. It's important for us to place dogs in a home that's suitable. You may be a stellar owner but possibly not a good fit for the dog you were first interested in adopting. We're not trying to offend anyone, we're trying to set everyone up for success. We're a best fit rescue and will verify your vet and personal references.

Adoption Process:

Step 1: Complete a "no obligation" application on our website, www.pawprintsnky.com

Step 2: PawPrints will review the application, verifying Vet and personal references as well as landlord requirements/restrictions (if applicable)

Step 3: IF your application is approved, we will call you to schedule a meet and greet for you to meet the pet.

Step 4: If the meet and greet goes well, we will schedule the home visit.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 7/5/2019
Reason for being in rescue: found as a stray in SC
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? none noted
Weight: est 50 lbs

Height: est 17" at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? We are seeking a home with an experienced dog owner and someone who is home more than they're away. Bixby needs another confident dog in the home. He is very active and needs a family that can provide the physical and mental stimulation that a young dog needs. Bixby is not for a first time dog owner.

What is my personality like? Bixby is a happy, sweet pup! He is a very smart puppy and learns things very quickly. He has done excellent with his house training! He lives with many other dogs of all shapes and sizes and gets along well with all of them. He would love to have another dog in the home to play with and keep him company. Bixby would probably do best with another dog similar in size and stature as he likes to play rough sometimes. Bixby is currently working on his leash training and goes for walks three to four times a week. Bixby has also gone on off leash trail walks in the woods and absolutely loves it! He stays with his foster brothers and sisters and doesn't go out of sight. Bixby would be a great addition an active family looking for a young dog.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Bixby can be nervous meeting new people. Once he warms up he is all yours.

Other tips and tidbits: Bixby's estimated birthday is 3/13/2019.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Brianne (Bree). I'm an American Bulldog mix. My foster mom says I'm a survivor. Here's a little bit about me: Likes: a soft place to lay down and relax. I like other things like food and rolling in the grass, but nothing comes close to my love of simply relaxing. I had a hard start to life. My puppies and I were living under a house. We were taken in by the reacue and I underwent heartworm treatment. I am happy to be HW- now. It took a while to trust people. I am happiest when I have my humans close by, but not necessarily touching me. I just like to relax knowing they are there. Dislikes: thunder, fireworks, being cold, too much affection (I'm shy and still learning to accept love), dominant female dogs, and the sound of motorcycles and 4-wheelers.

My adoption fee is $200 Houston area or $550 for out of state (includes adoption fee, health certificate, and transport fees. Fill out an app at www.soca-fbc.org/adoptables.

animal.description:
If we could describe Socks in 5 words we'd say: Loyal. Obedient. Friendly. Loving. Goofball...(Yes GOOFBALL! or is goof ball 2 words? either way he is one) Since the day he came to us, all 65-70 lbs of Socks has been a barrel of fun. He loves to cuddle and give friendly kisses any chance he can. He is the sweetest, most loving dog that just wants to be shown love from a devoted owner. He'd love you to take him on walks and give him lots of belly rubs. And he'll never ever turn down the opportunity to play fetch. Socks walks well on a leash, knows sit, wait, place command and likes to please. Socks is looking for an owner that will show him as much love as he is always willing to give. With structure, consistent rules and discipline, Socks is a joy to have around. Socks is around ten years old, black male, pitbull lab mix, neutered with all of his shots and potty trained. He needs to be the ONLY dog in the house, no cats and prefers one on one attention rather than the overwhelming hubbub of dog parks. 

Socks: male, black and white, 65 lbs, Lab Mix (mixed with pitbull maybe but his records state lab mix), up to date on his shots, neutered, chipped, fully trained and 9 1/2 years old.

Socks is the perfect family dog that is fully trained. He is extremely submissive to people (He can shy and bows down to you upon meeting) and is extremely eager to please. He does yearn to have all the attention on him since he can be a bit territorial when it comes to other pets. Therefore, he should be the only pet in the home.

He knows how to use the doggy door and he hasnt had a single accident inside ever. He is great in car rides and does well on a leash. He is not destructive and is really only interested in toys and treats but knows not to beg for food. If his age might be a concern, he is energetic and LOVES being playful..for active families, he will fit right in! He is great with children.

He is a low maintenance dog, super calm and really just wants to be next to his human relaxing and cuddling much of the time. His coat is silky and shiny and he does not shed much. He is not a messy boy, not a digger or has any bad habits. 

He is a great addition to any family because he is so quick to adjust! He has deep brown eyes that penetrate your soul and he gives all his trust and love to you the moment he meets you. Give this gentle and very loyal boy a chance.

animal.description: Otto was at a rural shelter and about to be put down because he was so afraid. He is now in a foster home and is a very small guy with a big heart. He does not fight other dogs but he is "the big man on campus" and lets it be known by growling.. He would love an older person who can just hold him and love on him but he will make a great companion for almost anyone.

animal.description: Poppy is a sweet yet nervous girl who needs help feeling comfortable with new things. Poppy loves to play with balanced dogs and typically does not have a problem with most dogs but does not mix well with fearful dogs as herself. Poppy does not mix well with other fearful dogs. She tends to digress in those packs. She does well around people she knows and gets nervous around new people. The key is to use some structure to allow her some time to feel comfortable. She does best when she is in the background and when you split her focus in uncomfortable situations. I usually use her canine friends, walks, and sometimes muzzles to speed up the time she needs to feel comfortable. She is a great girl and loves attention. She has spent lots of time with children here. It took a little time for her to be comfortable with them. Now she loves them all and looks forward to their affection. Poppy needs an environment that allows her time to get comfortable. She also needs someone that advocates for her. She loves exercising and would love to walk at least 4 days a week. She does not need to walk too far. Most walks that are a mile or less do the trick for her. Poppy loves to chase and be chased by her canine friends. She also loves to wrestle with trusted canine friends. She loves to chew bones and toys. Poppy also loves to have a dog bed. Regular exercise and activity stops that. Poppy walks very nicely but can get nervous enough to react when some people walk by. Poppy tends to warm up to women faster than men. Poppy's dream day would include some play time, affection, and lots of nap time. She loves to just hang out and nap with the group.
animal.name: Poppy

Carly is a Blood hound mix. She is 7 years old and weighs about 65lbs. The only reason she needs a new home is because her only owner had to go into the hospital for a long time and there was no one left to care for her. She is an excellent family dog. She does very well with small children and multiple children. She is slow to introduce to other dogs, but does very well once we settles in. She currently live with one large and one small dog ( plus another foster puppy). She is not cat tested. 

She wants to be with her person all the time and she loves to hang her head out the car window on rides. She is crate trained, kennel trained, house trained and walks well on a leash. She is very quiet in the house once she settles into a routine. Carly like to spend her days lounging on her oversized ottoman. She is a great dog that is super sweet and would love to have a forever person.
animal.name: Carly- Bloodhound

Java is a 6 year old Chihuahua mix who weighs around 11 pounds. He is a sweet boy who hasn't had the easiest life. When he came to Cody's he was skin and bones and extremely fearful. He is now at a healthy weight but is still not very trusting especially of men. He will need a patient owner that can put in the time to help him overcome his fears. He does get along with other dogs and hasn't bothered the cat. He is playful and very loving once he feels safe. Java would be best in a home with a yard, not a good fit for apartment homes. He's just looking for that one special person.

Koda is a 12 - 14 year old Chihuahua mix who weighs about 12 pounds. He is an alert, loving senior who tries to befriend everyone he meets. He gets along great with the other dogs in his foster home as well as the cat. He totally loved all the attention he received over the holidays especially the numerous belly rubs. There is a certain playfulness about him that makes you forget his age. He reminds me of the WalMart greeter in that he waits at the back door and welcomes the others as they come in. He would be a great companion for just about anyone. He does have some age related health issues that will need to be maintained but his personality and zest for life are well worth it.
